cvTermList.name: Abdomen
cvTermList.description: That portion of the body that lies between the thorax and the pelvis.

cvTermList.name: Abdominal adipose tissue
cvTermList.description: Fatty tissue in the region of the abdomen.

cvTermList.name: Adipocyte
cvTermList.description: Cells in the body that store fats, usually in the form of triglycerides. White adipocytes are the predominant type and found mostly in the abdominal cavity and subcutaneous tissue. Brown adipocytes are thermogenic cells that can be found in newborns of some species and hibernating mammals.

cvTermList.name: Adipose tissue
cvTermList.description: Specialized connective tissue composed of fat cells (adipocytes). It is the site of stored fats, usually in the form of triglycerides. In mammals, there are two types of adipose tissue, the white fat and the brown fat. Their relative distributions vary in different species with most adipose tissue being white.

cvTermList.name: Adrenal cortex
cvTermList.description: The outer layer of the adrenal gland. It is derived from mesoderm and comprised of three zones (outer zona glomerulosa, middle zona fasciculata, and inner zona reticularis) with each producing various steroids preferentially, such as aldosterone; hydrocortisone; dehydroepiandrosterone; and androstenedione. Adrenal cortex function is regulated by pituitary adrenocorticotropin.

cvTermList.name: Adrenal gland
cvTermList.description: A pair of glands located at the cranial pole of each of the two kidneys. Each adrenal gland is composed of two distinct endocrine tissues with separate embryonic origins, the adrenal cortex producing steroids and the adrenal medulla producing neurotransmitters.

cvTermList.name: Adrenal glomerulosa
cvTermList.description: The narrow subcapsular outer zone of the adrenal cortex. This zone produces a series of enzymes that convert pregnenolone to aldosterone. The final steps involve three successive oxidations by aldosterone synthase.

cvTermList.name: Adrenal medulla
cvTermList.description: The inner portion of the adrenal gland. Derived from ectoderm, adrenal medulla consists mainly of chromaffin cells that produces and stores a number of neurotransmitters, mainly adrenaline (epinephrine) and norepinephrine. The activity of the adrenal medulla is regulated by the sympathetic nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Airway epithelium
cvTermList.description: The mucous membrane lining the respiratory tract, including the nasal cavity; the larynx; the trachea; and the bronchi tree. The respiratory mucosa consists of various types of epithelial cells ranging from ciliated columnar to simple squamous, mucous goblet cells, and glands containing both mucous and serous cells.

cvTermList.name: Alveolar macrophage
cvTermList.description: Round, granular, mononuclear phagocytes found in the alveoli of the lungs. They ingest small inhaled particles resulting in degradation and presentation of the antigen to immunocompetent cells.

cvTermList.name: Alveolus
cvTermList.description: Small polyhedral outpouchings along the walls of the alveolar sacs, alveolar ducts and terminal bronchioles through the walls of which gas exchange between alveolar air and pulmonary capillary blood takes place. Tiny air sacs at the end of the bronchioles in the lungs.

cvTermList.name: Amnion
cvTermList.description: The innermost membranous sac that surrounds and protects the developing embryo which is bathed in the amniotic fluid. Amnion cells are secretory epithelial cells and contribute to the amniotic fluid.

cvTermList.name: Amniotic fluid
cvTermList.description: A clear, yellowish liquid that envelopes the fetus inside the sac of amnion. In the first trimester, it is likely a transudate of maternal or fetal plasma. In the second trimester, amniotic fluid derives primarily from fetal lung and kidney. Cells or substances in this fluid can be removed for prenatal diagnostic tests (amniocentesis).

cvTermList.name: Amygdala
cvTermList.description: Almond-shaped group of basal nuclei anterior to the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle of the brain, within the temporal lobe. The amygdala is part of the limbic system.

cvTermList.name: Aorta
cvTermList.description: The main trunk of the systemic arteries.

cvTermList.name: Aortic endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium lining the aorta.

cvTermList.name: Aortic smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: Smooth muscle of aorta.

cvTermList.name: Appendix glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of appendix epithelium. Example: Goblet cells; enterocytes or absorptive cells; enteroendocrine and M cells.

cvTermList.name: Appendix lymphoid tissue
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid tissue located in the appendix.

cvTermList.name: Appendix
cvTermList.description: A worm-like blind tube extension from the cecum.

cvTermList.name: Arachnoid membrane
cvTermList.description: A delicate membrane enveloping the brain and spinal cord. It lies between the pia mater and the dura mater. It is separated from the pia mater by the subarachnoid cavity which is filled with cerebrospinal fluid.

cvTermList.name: Artery smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: Smooth muscle of arteries.

cvTermList.name: Artery
cvTermList.description: The vessels carrying blood away from the heart.

cvTermList.name: Articular cartilage
cvTermList.description: A thin layer of cartilage, usually of hyaline, that covers the epiphysis where the bone forms a joint with another bone. Absorbs shock and reduces friction.

cvTermList.name: Articular chondrocyte
cvTermList.description: Chondrocyte forming the hyaline cartilage found in joints.

cvTermList.name: Ascending colon
cvTermList.description: The segment of large intestine between the cecum and the transverse colon. It passes cephalad from the cecum to the caudal surface of the right lobe of the liver where it bends sharply to the left, forming the right colic flexure.

cvTermList.name: Astrocyte
cvTermList.description: A class of large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system, the largest and most numerous neuroglial cells in the brain and spinal cord. Astrocytes (from star cells) are irregularly shaped with many long processes, including those with end feet which form the glial (limiting) membrane and directly and indirectly contribute to the blood-brain barrier. They regulate the extracellular ionic and chemical environment, and reactive astrocytes (along with microglia) respond to injury.

cvTermList.name: B-cell
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid cells concerned with humoral immunity. They are short-lived cells resembling bursa-derived lymphocytes of birds in their production of immunoglobulin upon appropriate stimulation.

cvTermList.name: Basal ganglia
cvTermList.description: Large subcortical nuclear masses derived from the telencephalon and located in the basal regions of the cerebral hemispheres.

cvTermList.name: Basophil
cvTermList.description: Granular leukocytes characterized by a relatively pale-staining, lobate nucleus and cytoplasm containing coarse dark-staining granules of variable size and stainable by basic dyes.

cvTermList.name: Bile duct
cvTermList.description: The channels that collect and transport the bile secretion from the bile canaliculi, the smallest branch of the biliary tract in the liver, through the bile ductules, the bile ducts out the liver, and to the gallbladder for storage.

cvTermList.name: Bile
cvTermList.description: An emulsifying agent produced in the liver and secreted into the duodenum. Its composition includes bile acids and salts; cholesterol; and electrolytes. It aids digestion of fats in the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Blastocyst
cvTermList.description: A post-morula preimplantation mammalian embryo that develops from a 32-cell stage into a fluid-filled hollow ball of over a hundred cells. A blastocyst has two distinctive tissues. The outer layer of trophoblasts gives rise to extra-embryonic tissues. The inner cell mass gives rise to the embryonic disc and eventual embryo proper.

cvTermList.name: Blood vessel
cvTermList.description: Any of the tubular vessels conveying the blood (arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins).

cvTermList.name: Blood
cvTermList.description: The body fluid that circulates in the cardiovascular system (blood vessels and blood capillaries) including plasma and blood cells.

cvTermList.name: Bone marrow stroma
cvTermList.description: The stroma of the bone marrow is the supporting tissue not directly involved in the primary function of hematopoiesis.

cvTermList.name: Bone marrow
cvTermList.description: The soft tissue filling the cavities of bones. Bone marrow exists in two types, yellow and red. Yellow marrow is found in the large cavities of large bones and consists mostly of fat cells and a few primitive blood cells. Red marrow is a hematopoietic tissue and is the site of production of erythrocytes and granular leukocytes. Bone marrow is made up of a framework of connective tissue containing branching fibers with the frame being filled with marrow cells.

cvTermList.name: Bone
cvTermList.description: Rigid organ that forms the skeletal components of the body. The tissues found in bones include bone tissue, bone marrow, endosteum and periosteum, nerves, blood vessels and cartilage.

cvTermList.name: Brain capillary
cvTermList.description: Capillaries of the blood-brain-barrier.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral cortex glial cell
cvTermList.description: Glial cell of cerebral cortex.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral cortex neuron
cvTermList.description: Neuron of cerebral cortex.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral cortex
cvTermList.description: The thin layer of gray matter on the surface of the cerebral hemisphere that develops from the telencephalon and folds into gyri. It reaches its highest development in man and is responsible for intellectual faculties and higher mental functions.

cvTermList.name: Brain endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium found in blood vessels of the blood-brain-barrier.

cvTermList.name: Brain stem
cvTermList.description: The part of the brain that connects the cerebral hemispheres with the spinal cord. It consists of the mesencephalon; pons; and medulla oblongata.

cvTermList.name: Brain
cvTermList.description: The part of central nervous system that is contained within the skull (cranium). Arising from the neural tube, the embryonic brain is comprised of three major parts including prosencephalon (the forebrain); mesencephalon (the midbrain); and rhombencephalon (the hindbrain). The developed brain consists of cerebrum; cerebellum; and other structures in the brain stem.

cvTermList.name: Bronchiolar epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the bronchioles. The larger bionchioles have a ciliated pseudostratified columnar epithelium that gradually transforms to a simple ciliated columnar epithelium as the duct narows. Small bronchioles have a simple cuboidal epithelium. The terminal bronchioles have a simple cuboidal epithelium in which Clara cells are found among the ciliated cells.

cvTermList.name: Bronchus epithelium
cvTermList.description: The respiratory bronchus is lined by respiratory epithelium comprising an admixture of pseudo stratified ciliated columnar epithelium, goblet cells (mucin producing cells also termed mucous cells) and basal cells that function as progenitor cells for both the ciliated columnar cells and goblet cells. Ciliated cells are about five times more numerous than goblet cells in the central airways and the ratio of ciliated cells increases in the smaller and peripheral bronchi (bronchioles) as the goblet cells diminish. The basal cells are more abundant in the proximal airways, where they form more or less, a continuous layer and gradually diminish in number in peripheral bronchi. Small clusters of neuroendocrine cells located within the bronchial epithelium called neuroepithelial bodies can be identified.

cvTermList.name: Bronchus
cvTermList.description: The larger air passages of the lungs arising from the terminal bifurcation of the trachea. They include the largest two primary bronchi which branch out into secondary bronchi, and tertiary bronchi which extend into bronchioles and pulmonary alveoli.

cvTermList.name: Brown adipose tissue
cvTermList.description: A thermogenic form of adipose tissue composed of brown adipocytes. It is found in newborns of many species including humans, and in hibernating mammals. Brown fat is richly vascularized, innervated, and densely packed with mitochondria which can generate heat directly from the stored lipids. Fat cells with dark coloration due to the densely packed mitochondria. They contain numerous small lipid droplets or vacuoles. Their stored lipids can be converted directly to energy as heat by the mitochondria .

cvTermList.name: Bulbourethral gland
cvTermList.description: Glands situated on each side of the prostate that secrete a fluid component of the seminal fluid into the urethra.

cvTermList.name: Central nervous system
cvTermList.description: The main information-processing organs of the nervous system, consisting of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.

cvTermList.name: Cajal-Retzius cell
cvTermList.description: The term Cajal Retzius cell is applied to reelin-producing neurons of the human embryonic marginal zone which display, as a salient feature, radial ascending processes that contact the pial surface, and a horizontal axon plexus located in the deep marginal zone.

cvTermList.name: Cancellous bone
cvTermList.description: Bone tissue that has the appearance of a sponge. The tissue is arranged as trabeculae forming a meshwork. The spaces of the meshwork are continuous and occupied by marrow and blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Capillary endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium lining capillaries.

cvTermList.name: Heart muscle cell
cvTermList.description: Striated muscle cells found in the heart. They are derived from cardiac myoblasts.

cvTermList.name: Carotid artery
cvTermList.description: Either of the two principal arteries on both sides of the neck that supply blood to the head and neck; each divides into two branches, the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.

cvTermList.name: Cartilage
cvTermList.description: A non-vascular form of connective tissue composed of chondrocytes embedded in a matrix that includes chondroitin sulfate and various types of fibrillar collagen. There are three major types: hyaline cartilage; fibrocartilage; and elastic cartilage.

cvTermList.name: Caudate nucleus
cvTermList.description: Elongated gray mass of the neostriatum located adjacent to the lateral ventricle of the brain.

cvTermList.name: Cecum
cvTermList.description: The blind sac or outpouching area of the large intestine that is below the entrance of the small intestine. It has a worm-like extension, the vermiform appendix.

cvTermList.name: Cementoblast
cvTermList.description: A large cell ranging in shape from cuboidal to squamous with a large central nucleus. The nucleus usually has a single nucleolus, which is active in the formation of cementum.

cvTermList.name: Cerebellum granular layer
cvTermList.description: The bottom thick layer of the cerebellar cortex. Is densely packed with granule cells, along with much smaller numbers of interneurons, mainly Golgi cells.

cvTermList.name: Cerebellum molecular layer
cvTermList.description: The top layer of the cerebellar cortex. Contains the flattened dendritic trees of Purkinje cells, along with the huge array of parallel fibers penetrating the Purkinje cell dendritic trees at right angles. This outermost layer of the cerebellar cortex also contains two types of inhibitory interneurons, stellate cells, and basket cells. Both stellate and basket cells form gabaergic synapses onto Purkinje cell dendrites.

cvTermList.name: Cerebellum
cvTermList.description: The part of brain that lies behind the brain stem in the posterior base of skull (posterior cranial fossa). It is also known as the little brain with convolutions similar to those of cerebral cortex, inner white matter, and deep cerebellar nuclei. Its function is to coordinate voluntary movements, maintain balance, and learn motor skills.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral artery
cvTermList.description: The arterial blood vessels supplying the cerebrum.

cvTermList.name: Cerebrospinal fluid
cvTermList.description: The fluid that is contained within the brain ventricles, the subarachnoid space and the central canal of the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Uterine cervix epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the uterine cervix. The portion of the uterine cervix epithelium that projects into the vagina is stratified squamous epithelium and the supravaginal portion is columnar epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Uterine cervix glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of uterine cervix epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Uterine cervix squamous cell
cvTermList.description: Squamous cell of uterine cervix epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Uterine cervix
cvTermList.description: The neck portion of the uterus between the lower isthmus and the vagina forming the cervical canal.

cvTermList.name: Chondrocyte
cvTermList.description: Polymorphic cells that form cartilage.

cvTermList.name: Chorioamniotic membrane
cvTermList.description: Amnionic and chorionic membranes considered together.

cvTermList.name: Chorionic membrane
cvTermList.description: The outermost extra-embryonic membrane surrounding the developing embryo. In reptiles and birds, it adheres to the shell and allows exchange of gases between the egg and its environment. In mammals, the chorion evolves into the fetal contribution of the placenta.

cvTermList.name: Choroid plexus
cvTermList.description: A villous structure of tangled masses of blood vessels contained within the third, lateral, and fourth ventricles of the brain. It regulates part of the production and composition of cerebrospinal fluid.

cvTermList.name: Cochlea
cvTermList.description: The part of the inner ear (labyrinth) that is concerned with hearing. It forms the anterior part of the labyrinth, as a snail-like structure that is situated almost horizontally anterior to the vestibular labyrinth.

cvTermList.name: Cochlear duct
cvTermList.description: A spiral tube that is firmly suspended in the bony shell-shaped part of the cochlea. This endolymph-filled cochlear duct begins at the vestibule and makes 2.5 turns around a core of spongy bone (the modiolus) thus dividing the perilymph-filled spiral canal into two channels, the scala vestibuli and the scala tympani.

cvTermList.name: Colon endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium found in colon blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Colon epithelium
cvTermList.description: Simple columnar epithelium lining the colon.

cvTermList.name: Colon glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of colon epithelium. Example: Goblet cells; enterocytes or absorptive cells; enteroendocrine and M cells.

cvTermList.name: Colon mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the large intestine mucosa lining the colon.

cvTermList.name: Colon smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: Smooth muscle of colon.

cvTermList.name: Colon
cvTermList.description: The segment of large intestine between the cecum and the rectum. It includes the ascending colon; the transverse colon; the descending colon; and the sigmoid colon.

cvTermList.name: Colostrum
cvTermList.description: The thin, yellow, serous fluid secreted by the mammary glands during pregnancy and immediately postpartum before lactation begins. It consists of immunologically active substances, white blood cells, water, protein, fat, and carbohydrates.

cvTermList.name: Cornea
cvTermList.description: The transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye consisting of five layers: stratified squamous corneal epithelium; bowman membrane; corneal stroma; descemet membrane; and mesenchymal corneal endothelium. It serves as the first refracting medium of the eye. It is structurally continuous with the sclera, avascular, receiving its nourishment by permeation through spaces between the lamellae, and is innervated by the ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve via the ciliary nerves and those of the surrounding conjunctiva which together form plexuses.

cvTermList.name: Corneal endothelium
cvTermList.description: Single layer of large flattened cells covering the surface of the cornea.

cvTermList.name: Corneal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Stratified squamous epithelium that covers the outer surface of the cornea. It is smooth and contains many free nerve endings.

cvTermList.name: Corneal fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Corneal fibroblast are located between each lamella of the in the corneal stroma.

cvTermList.name: Corneal stroma
cvTermList.description: The lamellated connective tissue constituting the thickest layer of the cornea between the Bowman and Descemet membranes.

cvTermList.name: Coronary arterial endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium lining the coronary artery.

cvTermList.name: Coronary artery
cvTermList.description: The veins and arteries of the heart.

cvTermList.name: Corpus callosum
cvTermList.description: Broad plate of dense myelinated fibers that reciprocally interconnect regions of the cortex in all lobes with corresponding regions of the opposite hemisphere. The corpus callosum is located deep in the longitudinal fissure.

cvTermList.name: Corpus luteum
cvTermList.description: The yellow body derived from the ruptured ovarian follicle after ovulation. The process of corpus luteum formation, luteinization, is regulated by luteinizing hormone.

cvTermList.name: Corpus striatum
cvTermList.description: Striped gray and white matter consisting of the neostriatum and paleostriatum (globus pallidus). It is located in front of and lateral to the thalamus in each cerebral hemisphere. The gray substance is made up of the caudate nucleus and the lentiform nucleus (the latter consisting of the globus pallidus and putamen). The white matter is the internal capsule.

cvTermList.name: Cytotoxic T-cell
cvTermList.description: Immunized T-lymphocytes which can directly destroy appropriate target cells. These cytotoxic lymphocytes may be generated in vitro in mixed lymphocyte cultures (mlc), in vivo during a graft-versus-host (gvh) reaction, or after immunization with an allograft, tumor cell or virally transformed or chemically modified target cell. The lytic phenomenon is sometimes referred to as cell-mediated lympholysis (cml). These CD8-positive cells are distinct from natural killer cells and natural killer T-cells. There are two effector phenotypes: TC1 and TC2.

cvTermList.name: Decidua placentalis
cvTermList.description: The hormone-responsive glandular layer of endometrium that sloughs off at each menstrual flow (decidua menstrualis) or at the termination of pregnancy. During pregnancy, the thickest part of the decidua forms the maternal portion of the placenta, thus named decidua placentalis. The thin portion of the decidua covering the rest of the embryo is the decidua capsularis.

cvTermList.name: Dendritic cell
cvTermList.description: Specialized cells of the hematopoietic system that have branch-like extensions. They are found throughout the lymphatic system, and in non-lymphoid tissues such as skin and the epithelia of the intestinal, respiratory, and reproductive tracts. They trap and process antigens, and present them to T-cells, thereby stimulating cell-mediated immunity. They are different from the non-hematopoietic follicular dendritic cells, which have a similar morphology and immune system function, but with respect to humoral immunity (antibody production).

cvTermList.name: Dental pulp
cvTermList.description: A richly vascularized and innervated connective tissue of mesodermal origin, contained in the central cavity of a tooth and delimited by the dentin, and having formative, nutritive, sensory, and protective functions.

cvTermList.name: Diaphragm
cvTermList.description: The musculofibrous partition that separates the thoracic cavity from the abdominal cavity. Contraction of the diaphragm increases the volume of the thoracic cavity aiding inhalation.

cvTermList.name: Diencephalon
cvTermList.description: The paired caudal parts of the prosencephalon from which the thalamus; hypothalamus; epithalamus; and subthalamus are derived.

cvTermList.name: Distal colon epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the distal colon.

cvTermList.name: Distal colon mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the large intestine mucosa lining the distal colon.

cvTermList.name: Distal colon
cvTermList.description: Includes the descending colon and sigmoid colon.

cvTermList.name: Ductus ejaculatorius
cvTermList.description: Paired structures in male anatomy. Each ejaculatory duct is formed by the union of the vas deferens with the duct of the seminal vesicle. They pass through the prostate, and empty into the urethra at the Colliculus seminalis. During ejaculation, semen passes through the ducts and exits the body via the penis.

cvTermList.name: Duodenal mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the small intestine mucosa lining the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Duodenum glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of duodenal epithelium. Example: Enterocytes, Goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells; Paneth cells; M cells; Brunner's gland cell.

cvTermList.name: Duodenum
cvTermList.description: The shortest and widest portion of the small intestine adjacent to the pylorus of the stomach. It is named for having the length equal to about the width of 12 fingers.

cvTermList.name: Ear
cvTermList.description: The hearing and equilibrium system of the body. It consists of three parts: the external ear, the middle ear, and the inner ear. Sound waves are transmitted through this organ where vibration is transduced to nerve signals that pass through the acoustic nerve to the central nervous system. The inner ear also contains the vestibular organ that maintains equilibrium by transducing signals to the vestibular nerve.

cvTermList.name: Ectoderm
cvTermList.description: The outer of the three germ layers of an embryo.

cvTermList.name: Embryo
cvTermList.description: The entities of developing animals in early stages. This stage lasts until the end of eighth week after conception.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic brain
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult brain. Example: neural crest, floor plate, embryonic rhombencephalon.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from embryo.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic head
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult head.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic heart
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult heart.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic kidney
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult kidney.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic liver
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult liver.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic lung fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from embryonic lung.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic lung
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult lung.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic spinal cord
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic stem cell
cvTermList.description: Cells derived from the blastocyst inner cell mass which forms before implantation in the uterine wall. They retain the ability to divide, proliferate and provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic testis
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult testis.

cvTermList.name: Enamel organ
cvTermList.description: Epithelial cells surrounding the dental papilla and differentiated into three layers: the inner enamel epithelium, consisting of ameloblasts which eventually form the enamel, and the enamel pulp and external enamel epithelium, both of which atrophy and disappear before and upon eruption of the tooth, respectively.

cvTermList.name: Endoderm
cvTermList.description: The inner of the three germ layers of an embryo.

cvTermList.name: Endometrium stroma
cvTermList.description: The stroma of the uterus contains loose connective tissue, fibroblasts, blood vessels, lymphatic vessels, and nerves.

cvTermList.name: Endometrium
cvTermList.description: The mucous membrane lining of the uterine cavity that is hormonally responsive during the menstrual cycle and pregnancy. The endometrium undergoes cyclic changes that characterize menstruation. After successful fertilization, it serves to sustain the developing embryo.

cvTermList.name: Endothelium
cvTermList.description: A layer of epithelium that lines the heart, blood vessels (blood vessel vascular endothelium), lymph vessels (lymphatic vessel vascular endothelium), and the serous cavities of the body.

cvTermList.name: Eosinophil
cvTermList.description: Granular leukocytes with a nucleus that usually has two lobes connected by a slender thread of chromatin, and cytoplasm containing coarse, round granules that are uniform in size and stainable by eosin.

cvTermList.name: Epidermis
cvTermList.description: The external, non-vascular layer of the skin. It is made up, from within outward, of five layers of epithelium: (1) basal layer (stratum basale epidermidis); (2) spinous layer (stratum spinosum epidermidis); (3) granular layer (stratum granulosum epidermidis); (4) clear layer (stratum lucidum epidermidis); and (5) horny layer (stratum corneum epidermidis).

cvTermList.name: Epididymis glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of epididymal epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Epididymis
cvTermList.description: The convoluted cord like structure attached to the posterior of the testis. Epididymis consists of the head (caput), the body (corpus), and the tail (cauda). A network of ducts leaving the testis joins into a common epididymal tubule proper which provides the transport, storage, and maturation of spermatozoa.

cvTermList.name: Epithelium
cvTermList.description: One or more layers of epithelial cells, supported by the basal lamina, which covers the inner or outer surfaces of the body.

cvTermList.name: Erythroblast
cvTermList.description: Immature, nucleated erythrocytes occupying the stage of erythropoiesis that follows formation of erythroid precursor cells and precedes formation of reticulocytes. The normal series is called normoblasts. Cells called megaloblasts are a pathologic series of erythroblasts.

cvTermList.name: Erythrocyte
cvTermList.description: Red blood cells. Mature erythrocytes are non-nucleated, biconcave disks containing hemoglobin whose function is to transport oxygen.

cvTermList.name: Exocrine pancreas
cvTermList.description: The major component (about 80%) of the pancreas composed of acinar functional units of tubular and spherical cells. The acinar cells synthesize and secrete several digestive enzymes such as trypsinogen; lipase; amylase; and ribonuclease. Secretion from the exocrine pancreas drains into the pancreatic ductal system and empties into the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Extraocular muscle
cvTermList.description: The muscles that move the eye. Included in this group are the medial rectus, lateral rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, inferior oblique, superior oblique, musculus orbitalis, and levator palpebrae superioris.

cvTermList.name: Eye vitreous humor
cvTermList.description: The transparent, semigelatinous substance that fills the cavity behind the crystalline lens of the eye and in front of the retina. It is contained in a thin hyoid membrane and forms about four fifths of the optic globe.

cvTermList.name: Eye
cvTermList.description: The organ of sight or vision.

cvTermList.name: Femoral artery
cvTermList.description: The main artery of the thigh, a continuation of the external iliac artery.

cvTermList.name: Femur
cvTermList.description: The longest and largest bone of the skeleton, it is situated between the hip and the knee.

cvTermList.name: Fetal B-cell
cvTermList.description: B-cell from fetus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal adrenal gland
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult adrenal gland.

cvTermList.name: Fetal astrocyte
cvTermList.description: Astrocyte from fetus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal cerebral cortex
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult cerebral cortex.

cvTermList.name: Fetal brain
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult brain.

cvTermList.name: Fetal cartilage
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult cartilage.

cvTermList.name: Fetal colon
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult colon.

cvTermList.name: Fetal eye
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult eye.

cvTermList.name: Fetal fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from fetus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal heart
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult heart.

cvTermList.name: Fetal kidney
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult kidney.

cvTermList.name: Fetal liver
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult liver.

cvTermList.name: Fetal lung fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from fetal lung.

cvTermList.name: Fetal lung
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult lung.

cvTermList.name: Fetal muscle
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult muscle.

cvTermList.name: Fetal esophagus
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult oesophagus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal pancreas
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult pancreas.

cvTermList.name: Fetal retina
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult retina.

cvTermList.name: Fetal skeletal muscle
cvTermList.description: Skeletal muscle from fetus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal skin
cvTermList.description: Skin from fetus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal spinal cord
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Fetal spleen
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult spleen.

cvTermList.name: Fetal sternum
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult sternum.

cvTermList.name: Fetal testis
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult testis.

cvTermList.name: Fetal thymus
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult thymus.

cvTermList.name: Fetus
cvTermList.description: The unborn young of a viviparous mammal, in the postembryonic period, after the major structures have been outlined. In humans, the unborn young from the end of the eighth week after conception until birth, as distinguished from the earlier embryo, mammalian.

cvTermList.name: Fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Connective tissue cells which secrete an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules.

cvTermList.name: Foot sole
cvTermList.description: The sole is the bottom of the foot. In humans the sole of the foot is anatomically referred to as the plantar aspect.

cvTermList.name: Foot
cvTermList.description: The distal extremity of the leg in vertebrates, consisting of the tarsus (ankle); metatarsus; phalanges; and the soft tissues surrounding these bones.

cvTermList.name: Forebrain
cvTermList.description: The anterior of the three primitive cerebral vesicles of the embryonic brain arising from the neural tube. It subdivides to form diencephalon and telencephalon.

cvTermList.name: Foreskin fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from foreskin.

cvTermList.name: Foreskin keratinocyte
cvTermList.description: Keratinocyte from foreskin.

cvTermList.name: Foreskin
cvTermList.description: The double-layered skin fold that covers the glans penis, the head of the penis.

cvTermList.name: Frontal lobe
cvTermList.description: The anterior part of the cerebral hemisphere.

cvTermList.name: Gall bladder glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of gall bladder epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Gall bladder
cvTermList.description: A storage reservoir for bile secretion. Gallbladder allows the delivery of bile acids at a high concentration and in a controlled manner, via the cystic duct to the duodenum, for degradation of dietary lipid.

cvTermList.name: Gamete
cvTermList.description: Haploid cell that fuses with another gamete during fertilization in organisms that reproduce sexually. Is a mature germ cell.

cvTermList.name: Ganglion
cvTermList.description: Clusters of multipolar neurons surrounded by a capsule of loosely organized connective tissue located outside the central nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Stomach mucosa
cvTermList.description: Lining of the stomach, consisting of an inner epithelium, a middle lamina propria, and an outer muscularis mucosae. The surface cells produce mucus that protects the stomach from attack by digestive acid and enzymes. When the epithelium invaginates into the lamina propria at various region of the stomach (cardia; gastric fundus; and pylorus), different tubular gastric glands are formed. These glands consist of cells that secrete mucus, enzymes, hydrochloric acid, or hormones.

cvTermList.name: Gastrointestinal tract
cvTermList.description: Generally refers to the digestive structures stretching from the mouth to anus, but does not include the accessory glandular organs (liver; biliary tract; pancreas).

cvTermList.name: Germ cell
cvTermList.description: The reproductive cells in multicellular organisms at various stages during gametogenesis.

cvTermList.name: Glial cell
cvTermList.description: The non-neuronal cells of the nervous system. They not only provide physical support, but also respond to injury, regulate the ionic and chemical composition of the extracellular milieu, participate in the blood-brain barrier and blood-retinal barrier, form the myelin insulation of nervous pathways, guide neuronal migration during development, and exchange metabolites with neurons. Neuroglia have high-affinity transmitter uptake systems, voltage-dependent and transmitter-gated ion channels, and can release transmitters, but their role in signaling (as in many other functions) is unclear.

cvTermList.name: Granulocyte
cvTermList.description: Leukocytes with abundant granules in the cytoplasm. They are divided into three groups according to the staining properties of the granules: neutrophilic, eosinophilic, and basophilic. Mature granulocytes are the neutrophils; eosinophils; and basophils.

cvTermList.name: Dermal papilla
cvTermList.description: A projection of the dermis into the epidermis.

cvTermList.name: Hair follicle
cvTermList.description: A tube-like invagination of the epidermis from which the hair shaft develops and into which sebaceous glands open. The hair follicle is lined by a cellular inner and outer root sheath of epidermal origin and is invested with a fibrous sheath derived from the dermis. Follicles of very long hairs extend into the subcutaneous layer of tissue under the skin.

cvTermList.name: Hair root
cvTermList.description: The hair root or bulb is the inferior segment of the hair follicle. The base of the bulb is invaginated by the dermal papilla.

cvTermList.name: Hair
cvTermList.description: A filament-like structure consisting of a shaft which projects to the surface of the skin from a root which is softer than the shaft and lodges in the cavity of a hair follicle. It is found on most surfaces of the body.

cvTermList.name: Head
cvTermList.description: The anterior and superior part of a human bearing the mouth, the brain and sensory organs.

cvTermList.name: Heart atrium
cvTermList.description: The chambers of the heart, to which the blood returns from the circulation.

cvTermList.name: Heart left ventricle
cvTermList.description: The left ventricle is one of four chambers (two atria and two ventricles) in the human heart. It receives oxygenated blood from the left atrium via the mitral valve, and pumps it into the aorta via the aortic valve.

cvTermList.name: Heart muscle
cvTermList.description: The muscle tissue of the heart. It is composed of striated, involuntary muscle cells (myocytes, cardiac) connected to form the contractile pump to generate blood flow.

cvTermList.name: Heart right ventricle
cvTermList.description: The right ventricle is one of four chambers (two atria and two ventricles) in the human heart. It receives deoxygenated blood from the right atrium via the tricuspid valve, and pumps it into the pulmonary artery via the pulmonary valve and pulmonary trunk.

cvTermList.name: Heart ventricle
cvTermList.description: The lower right and left chambers of the heart. The right ventricle pumps venous blood into the lungs and the left ventricle pumps oxygenated blood into the systemic arterial circulation.

cvTermList.name: Heart
cvTermList.description: The hollow, muscular organ that maintains the circulation of the blood.

cvTermList.name: Helper T-cell
cvTermList.description: A effector T cell that provides help in the form of secreted cytokines to other immune cells.

cvTermList.name: Hematopoietic stem cell
cvTermList.description: Progenitor cells from which all blood cells derive.

cvTermList.name: Hematopoietic and immune systems
cvTermList.description: Tissues and organs involved in blood cell production and immune response.

cvTermList.name: Hepatic stellate cell
cvTermList.description: A star-shaped cell in the liver associated with the development of fibrosis. When stellate cells are activated in response to an injury, they proliferate and synthesize large amounts of extracellular matrix which results in deposition of scar or fibrous tissue. Perisinusoidal cells of the liver, located in the space of Disse between hepatocytes and sinusoidal endothelial cells.

cvTermList.name: Hepatocyte
cvTermList.description: The main structural component of the liver. They are specialized epithelial cells that are organized into interconnected plates called lobules.

cvTermList.name: Hindbrain
cvTermList.description: It consists of the medulla oblongata, cerebellum, pons and the fourth ventricle.

cvTermList.name: Hippocampus glial cell
cvTermList.description: Glial cell of hippocampus.

cvTermList.name: Hippocampus neuron
cvTermList.description: Neuron of hippocampus.

cvTermList.name: Hippocampus
cvTermList.description: A curved elevation of gray matter extending the entire length of the floor of the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle. The hippocampus, subiculum, and dentate gyrus constitute the hippocampal formation. Sometimes authors include the entorhinal cortex in the hippocampal formation.

cvTermList.name: Hypothalamus
cvTermList.description: Ventral part of the diencephalon extending from the region of the optic chiasm to the caudal border of the mammillary bodies and forming the inferior and lateral walls of the third ventricle.

cvTermList.name: Ileal mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the small intestine mucosa lining the ileum.

cvTermList.name: Ileum
cvTermList.description: The distal and narrowest portion of the small intestine, between the jejunum and the ileocecal valve of the large intestine.

cvTermList.name: Inner ear vestibule
cvTermList.description: An oval, bony chamber of the inner ear, part of the bony labyrinth. It is continuous with bony cochlea anteriorly, and semicircular canals posteriorly. The vestibule contains two communicating sacs (utricle and saccule) of the balancing apparatus. The oval window on its lateral wall is occupied by the base of the stapes of the middle ear.

cvTermList.name: Inner ear
cvTermList.description: The essential part of the hearing organ consists of two labyrinthine compartments: the bony labyrinth and the membranous labyrinth. The bony labyrinth is a complex of three interconnecting cavities or spaces (cochlea; vestibular labyrinth; and semicircular canals) in the temporal bone. Within the bony labyrinth lies the membranous labyrinth which is a complex of sacs and tubules (cochlear duct; saccule and utricle; and semicircular ducts) forming a continuous space enclosed by epithelium and connective tissue. These spaces are filled with labyrinthine fluids of various compositions.

cvTermList.name: Intestine
cvTermList.description: The section of the alimentary canal from the stomach to the anal canal. It includes the large intestine and small intestine.

cvTermList.name: Iris
cvTermList.description: The most anterior portion of the uveal layer, separating the anterior chamber from the posterior. It consists of two layers - the stroma and the pigmented epithelium. Color of the iris depends on the amount of melanin in the stroma on reflection from the pigmented epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Jejunal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Part of the small intestine epithelium lining the jejunum.

cvTermList.name: Jejunal mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the small intestine mucosa lining the jejunum.

cvTermList.name: Jejunal smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: Smooth muscle of jejunum.

cvTermList.name: Jejunum
cvTermList.description: The middle portion of the small intestine, between duodenum and ileum. It represents about 2/5 of the remaining portion of the small intestine below duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Jugular vein endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium lining the jugular vein.

cvTermList.name: Jugular vein
cvTermList.description: Veins in the neck which drain the brain, face, and neck into the brachiocephalic or subclavian veins.

cvTermList.name: Keratinocyte
cvTermList.description: Epidermal cells which synthesize keratin and undergo characteristic changes as they move upward from the basal layers of the epidermis to the cornified (horny) layer of the skin. Successive stages of differentiation of the keratinocytes forming the epidermal layers are basal cell, spinous or prickle cell, and the granular cell.

cvTermList.name: Kidney cortex
cvTermList.description: The outer zone of the kidney, beneath the capsule, consisting of kidney glomerulus; kidney tubules, distal; and kidney tubules, proximal.

cvTermList.name: Renal distal tubule
cvTermList.description: The portion of renal tubule that begins from the enlarged segment of the ascending limb of the loop of Henle. It reenters the kidney cortex and forms the convoluted segments of the distal tubule.

cvTermList.name: Kidney epithelium
cvTermList.description: Depending on the kidney structure the epithelium is simple cuboidal (with or without microvilli) or simple squamous.

cvTermList.name: Kidney inner medulla
cvTermList.description: The part of the renal medulla that is farthest from the cortex. Each pyramid of the kidney medulla is dived into an outer medulla (adjacent to the cortex) and an inner medulla. The outer medulla is subdivided into an inner stripe and outer stripe.

cvTermList.name: Kidney outer medulla
cvTermList.description: The part of the renal medulla that is nearest to the cortex. Each pyramid of the kidney medulla is dived into an outer medulla (adjacent to the cortex) and an inner medulla. The outer medulla is subdivided into an inner stripe and outer stripe.

cvTermList.name: Renal proximal tubule
cvTermList.description: The renal tubule portion that extends from the bowman capsule in the kidney cortex into the kidney medulla. The proximal tubule consists of a convoluted proximal segment in the cortex, and a distal straight segment descending into the medulla where it forms the U-shaped loop of Henle.

cvTermList.name: Renal tubule
cvTermList.description: Long convoluted tubules in the nephrons. They collect filtrate from blood passing through the kidney glomerulus and process this filtrate into urine. Each renal tubule consists of a bowman capsule, proximal kidney tubule, loop of Henle, distal kidney tubule and kidney collecting duct leading to the central cavity of the kidney that connects to the ureter.

cvTermList.name: Kidney
cvTermList.description: Body organ that filters blood for the secretion of urine and that regulates ion concentrations.

cvTermList.name: Lacrimal gland
cvTermList.description: The tear-forming and tear-conducting system which includes the lacrimal glands, eyelid margins, conjunctival sac, and the tear drainage system.

cvTermList.name: Lactating mammary gland
cvTermList.description: Mammary gland in period of lactation.

cvTermList.name: Larynx
cvTermList.description: A tubular organ of voice production. It is located in the anterior neck, superior to the trachea and inferior to the tongue and hyoid bone.

cvTermList.name: Lateral ventricle glial cell
cvTermList.description: Glial cell of lateral ventricle.

cvTermList.name: Lateral ventricle neuron
cvTermList.description: Neuron of lateral ventricle.

cvTermList.name: Lateral ventricle
cvTermList.description: Cavity in each of the cerebral hemispheres derived from the cavity of the embryonic neural tube. They are separated from each other by the septum pellucidum, and each communicates with the third ventricle by the foramen of Monro, through which also the choroid plexuses (choroid plexus) of the lateral ventricles become continuous with that of the third ventricle.

cvTermList.name: Lens cortex
cvTermList.description: The portion of the crystalline lens surrounding the nucleus and bound anteriorly by the epithelium and posteriorly by the capsule. It contains lens fibers and amorphous, intercellular substance.

cvTermList.name: Lens epithelium
cvTermList.description: Simple cuboidal epithelium located in the anterior portion of the lens between the lens capsule and the lens fibers. The lens epithelium regulates homeostatic functions of the lens. Lens epithelial cells differentiate into lens fibers.

cvTermList.name: Lens fibers
cvTermList.description: One of the three principal components of the lens (the others being the lens capsule and subcapsular epithelium). They develop from the subcapsular epithelial cells. The lens fibers form the bulk of the lens. They are long, thin, transparent cells, firmly packed. As they developed they lose their nucleus and other organelles and become filled with crystallin protein.

cvTermList.name: Lens
cvTermList.description: A transparent, biconvex structure of the eye, enclosed in a capsule and situated behind the iris and in front of the vitreous humor (vitreous body). It is slightly overlapped at its margin by the ciliary processes. Adaptation by the ciliary body is crucial for ocular accommodation.

cvTermList.name: Leptomeninges
cvTermList.description: The two innermost layers of tissue that cover the brain and spinal cord, the arachnoid mater and the pia mater.

cvTermList.name: Leukocyte
cvTermList.description: White blood cells. These include granular leukocytes (basophils; eosinophils; and neutrophils) as well as non-granular leukocytes (lymphocytes and monocytes).

cvTermList.name: Leydig cell
cvTermList.description: Steroid-producing cells in the interstitial tissue of the testis. They are under the regulation of pituitary hormones, luteinizing hormone or interstitial cell-stimulating hormone. Testosterone is the major androgen (androgens) produced.

cvTermList.name: Limb
cvTermList.description: A body region referring to an upper or lower extremity.

cvTermList.name: Lip
cvTermList.description: Either of the two fleshy, full-blooded margins of the mouth.

cvTermList.name: Liver
cvTermList.description: A triangular-shaped organ located under the diaphragm in the right hypochondrium. It is the largest internal organ of the body, weighting up to 2 kg. Metabolism and bile secretion are its main functions. It is composed of cells which have the ability to regenerate.

cvTermList.name: Lung endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium found in lung blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Lung fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from lung.

cvTermList.name: Lung macrophage
cvTermList.description: Circulating macrophages and tissue macrophages (alveolar macrophages) of lung.

cvTermList.name: Lung
cvTermList.description: Either of the pair of organs occupying the cavity of the thorax that effect the aeration of the blood.

cvTermList.name: Lymph node germinal center cell
cvTermList.description: The germinal center or reaction center is the activated center of a lymphoid follicle in secondary lymphoid tissue where B-lymphocytes are stimulated by antigens and helper T cells (T-lymphocytes, helper-inducer) to generate memory cells. Here, the germinal center of a lymph node.

cvTermList.name: Lymph node lymphoid cell
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid cell located in lymph nodes.

cvTermList.name: Lymph node
cvTermList.description: They are oval or bean shaped bodies (1 - 30 mm in diameter) located along the lymphatic system. A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found through out the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection.

cvTermList.name: Lymph
cvTermList.description: A clear, transparent, sometimes faintly yellow and slightly opalescent fluid that is collected from the tissues throughout the body, flows in the lymphatic vessels (through the lymph nodes), and is eventually added to the venous blood circulation. Lymph consists of a clear liquid portion, varying numbers of white blood cells (chiefly lymphocytes), and a few red blood cells.

cvTermList.name: Lymphoblast
cvTermList.description: An immature lymphocyte that has enlarged in response to antigenic stimulation.

cvTermList.name: Lymphocyte
cvTermList.description: White blood cells formed in the body's lymphoid tissue. The nucleus is round or ovoid with coarse, irregularly clumped chromatin while the cytoplasm is typically pale blue with azurophilic (if any) granules. Most lymphocytes can be classified as either T or B (with subpopulations of each), or natural killer cells.

cvTermList.name: Lymphoid cell
cvTermList.description: Cells of the lymphoid lineage. Lymphocytes at different stages of maturation resident at the bone marrow, blood or lymphoid tissues.

cvTermList.name: Lymphoid tissue
cvTermList.description: Specialized tissues that provide fixed locations within the body where a variety of lymphocytes can form, mature and multiply. The lymphoid tissues are connected by a network of lymphatic vessels.

cvTermList.name: Macrophage
cvTermList.description: The relatively long-lived phagocytic cell of mammalian tissues that are derived from blood monocytes. Main types are peritoneal macrophages; alveolar macrophages; histiocytes; kupffer cells of the liver; and osteoclasts. They may further differentiate within chronic inflammatory lesions to epithelioid cells or may fuse to form foreign body giant cells or langhans giant cells.

cvTermList.name: Mammary epithelium
cvTermList.description: The epithelium that lines the lactiferous ducts and the secretory alveoli. The mammary epithelium in the lactiferous duct is a two layered epithelium. The basal cells are cuboidal and the superficial cells are columnar. Branches of the lactiferous duct are lined with a simple cuboidal epithelium. The secretory alveoli are lined by a cuboidal or columnar epithelium. During the first half of pregnancy, the epithelium undergoes considerable growth leading to the formation of new terminal branches of ducts and of alveoli. The mammary glands continue to grow during the second half of pregnancy due to increases in the height of epithelial cells and an expansion of the lumen of the alveoli. Glandular tissue in the breast of human that is under the influence of hormones such as estrogens; progestins; and prolactin. In women, after parturition, the mammary glands secrete milk for the nourishment of the young.

cvTermList.name: Mammary fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from breast.

cvTermList.name: Mammary gland glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of mammary epithelium. Example: glandular cells of large and intermediate ducts, glandular cells in terminal ducts.

cvTermList.name: Mammary gland
cvTermList.description: Glandular tissue in the breast of human that is under the influence of hormones such as estrogens, progestins and prolactin. In women, after parturition, the mammary glands secrete milk for the nourishment of the young.

cvTermList.name: Mast cell
cvTermList.description: Granulated cells that are found in almost all tissues, most abundantly in the skin and the gastrointestinal tract. Like the basophils, mast cells contain large amounts of histamine and heparin. Unlike basophils, mast cells normally remain in the tissues and do not circulate in the blood. Mast cells, derived from the bone marrow stem cells, are regulated by the stem cell factor.

cvTermList.name: Medulla oblongata
cvTermList.description: The lower portion of the brain stem. It is inferior to the pons and anterior to the cerebellum. Medulla oblongata serves as a relay station between the brain and the spinal cord, and contains centers for regulating respiratory, vasomotor, cardiac, and reflex activities.

cvTermList.name: Megakaryoblast
cvTermList.description: The parent cells that give rise to cells in the megakaryocyte lineage, and ultimately blood platelets.

cvTermList.name: Megakaryocyte
cvTermList.description: Very large bone marrow cells which release mature blood platelets.

cvTermList.name: Melanocyte
cvTermList.description: Mammalian pigment cells that produce melanins, pigments found mainly in the epidermis, but also in the eyes and the hair, by a process called melanogenesis. Coloration can be altered by the number of melanocytes or the amount of pigment produced and stored in the organelles called melanosomes. The large non-mammalian melanin-containing cells are called melanophores.

cvTermList.name: Meninges
cvTermList.description: The three membranes that cover the brain and the spinal cord. They are the dura mater, the arachnoid, and the pia mater.

cvTermList.name: Mesangial cell
cvTermList.description: Smooth muscle-like cells adhering to the wall of the small blood vessels of the kidney at the glomerulus and along the vascular pole of the glomerulus in the juxtaglomerular apparatus. They are myofibroblasts with contractile and phagocytic properties. These cells and their mesangial extracellular matrix constitute the glomerular mesangium.

cvTermList.name: Mesenchyme
cvTermList.description: Mesenchyme is a type of tissue characterized by loosely associated cells that lack polarity and are surrounded by a large extracellular matrix. Mesenchymal cells are able to develop into the tissues of the lymphatic and circulatory systems, as well as connective tissues throughout the body, such as bone and cartilage.

cvTermList.name: Mesenchymal stem cell
cvTermList.description: Cells that can develop into distinct mesenchymal tissue such as bone; tendons; muscles; adipose tissue; cartilage; nerve tissue; and blood and blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Mesoderm
cvTermList.description: The middle germ layer of an embryo derived from three paired mesenchymal aggregates along the neural tube.

cvTermList.name: Mesonephros
cvTermList.description: One of a pair of excretory organs (mesonephroi) which grow caudally to the first pair (pronephroi) during development. Mesonephroi are the permanent kidneys in adult amphibians and fish. In higher vertebrates, proneprhoi and most of mesonephroi degenerate with the appearance of metanephroi. The remaining ducts become wolffian ducts.

cvTermList.name: Mesothelium
cvTermList.description: Simple squamous epithelium lining the closed cavities of the body, such as the abdominal, thoracic and pericardial cavities.

cvTermList.name: Microglia
cvTermList.description: The third type of glial cell, along with astrocytes and oligodendrocytes (which together form the macroglia). Microglia vary in appearance depending on developmental stage, functional state, and anatomical location; subtype terms include ramified, perivascular, ameboid, resting, and activated. Microglia clearly are capable of phagocytosis and play an important role in a wide spectrum of neuropathologies. They have also been suggested to act in several other roles including in secretion (e.g., of cytokines and neural growth factors), in immunological processing (e.g., antigen presentation), and in central nervous system development and remodeling.

cvTermList.name: Midbrain
cvTermList.description: The middle of the three primitive cerebral vesicles of the embryonic brain. Without further subdivision, midbrain develops into a short, constricted portion connecting the pons and the diencephalon. Midbrain contains two major parts, the dorsal tectum mesencephali and the ventral tegmentum mesencephali, housing components of auditory, visual, and other sensorimoter systems.

cvTermList.name: Middle ear mucosa
cvTermList.description: One of the three layers of the tympanic membrane, the others being the skin of the external ear canal and the core of radially and circularly arranged collagen fibers.

cvTermList.name: Milk
cvTermList.description: The white liquid secreted by the mammary glands. It contains proteins, sugar, lipids, vitamins, and minerals.

cvTermList.name: Molar
cvTermList.description: The most posterior teeth on either side of the jaw, totaling eight in the deciduous dentition (2 on each side, upper and lower), and usually 12 in the permanent dentition (three on each side, upper and lower). They are grinding teeth, having large crowns and broad chewing surfaces.

cvTermList.name: Monoblast
cvTermList.description: Parent cells in the lineage that gives rise to monocytes and macrophages.

cvTermList.name: Monocyte
cvTermList.description: Large, phagocytic mononuclear leukocytes produced in the vertebrate bone marrow and released into the blood; contain a large, oval or somewhat indented nucleus surrounded by voluminous cytoplasm and numerous organelles.

cvTermList.name: Muscle fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from muscle organ.

cvTermList.name: Muscle
cvTermList.description: Contractile tissue that produces movement in animals.

cvTermList.name: Myeloid cell
cvTermList.description: The classes of bone marrow-derived blood cells in the monocytic series (monocytes and their precursors) and granulocytic series (granulocytes and their precursors).

cvTermList.name: Myoblast
cvTermList.description: Embryonic (precursor) cells of the myogenic lineage that develop from the mesoderm. They undergo proliferation, migrate to their various sites, and then differentiate into the appropriate form of myocytes.

cvTermList.name: Myometrium
cvTermList.description: The smooth muscle coat of the uterus, which forms the main mass of the organ.

cvTermList.name: Nasal cartilage
cvTermList.description: Hyaline cartilages in the nose. There are five major nasal cartilages including two lateral, two alar, and one septal.

cvTermList.name: Nasal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the nose. Each nose chamber is divided into three regions: vestibule, respiratory segment and olfactory segment. The vestibule is lined with stratified squamous epithelium. Where the vestibule ends, the stratified squamous epithelium becomes thinner and undergoes a transition to the pseudostratified epithelium that characterizes the respiratory segment. The ciliated, pseudostratified columnar epithelium of the respiratory segment is composed of ciliated cells, goblet cells, brush cells, small granule cells and basal cells. The epithelium of the respiratory segment of the nasal cavity is essentially the same as the epithelium lining most of the parts that follow in the conducting system. The olfactory epithelium lining the olfactory segment of the nasal cavity, like the epithelium of the respiratory segment, is also pseudostratified but contains different cell types: bipolar neurons olfactory cells, supporting or sustentacular cells, basal cells and brush cells. The mucous lining of the nasal cavity, including lining of the nostril (vestibule) and the olfactory mucosa. Nasal mucosa consists of ciliated cells, goblet cells, brush cells, small granule cells, basal cells (stem cells) and glands containing both mucous and serous cells.

cvTermList.name: Nasal mucosa
cvTermList.description: Mucosa that lines the nasal cavity.

cvTermList.name: Nasal mucus
cvTermList.description: Mucus secreted by the nasal mucosa.

cvTermList.name: Nasal vestibule
cvTermList.description: One of the three regions of a nose chamber (the others being the respiratory segment and the olfactory segment). It communicates with the external environment, and contains hairs and sebaceous glands for filtration and entrapment of particulate matter.

cvTermList.name: Nasopharyngeal epithelium
cvTermList.description: The two main types of epithelia lining the nasopharynx are stratified squamous (comprising approximately 60% of nasopharyngeal epithelium) and pseudostratified columnar respiratory-type epithelium containing ciliated cells, gobletcells and basal cells. The interphase between these two epithelia is sharp in some areas with an intermediate epithelium intervening in other areas.

cvTermList.name: Nasopharynx
cvTermList.description: The top portion of the pharynx situated posterior to the nose and superior to the soft palate. The nasopharynx is the posterior extension of the nasal cavities and has a respiratory function.

cvTermList.name: Natural killer cell
cvTermList.description: Bone marrow-derived lymphocytes that possess cytotoxic properties, classically directed against transformed and virus-infected cells. Unlike T cells and B cells NK cells are not antigen specific. The cytotoxicity of natural killer cells is determined by the collective signaling of an array of inhibitory and stimulatory cell surface receptors. A subset of T-lymphocytes referred to as natural killer T cells shares some of the properties of this cell type.

cvTermList.name: Neonatal skin
cvTermList.description: Skin from newborn.

cvTermList.name: Neural crest
cvTermList.description: The two longitudinal ridges along the primitive streak appearing near the end of gastrulation during development of nervous system (neurulation). The ridges are formed by folding of neural plate. Between the ridges is a neural groove which deepens as the fold become elevated. When the folds meet at midline, the groove becomes a closed tube, the neural tube.

cvTermList.name: Neuroectoderm
cvTermList.description: The region in the dorsal ectoderm of a chordate embryo that gives rise to the future central nervous system. Tissue in the neural plate is called the neuroectoderm, often used as a synonym of neural plate.

cvTermList.name: Neuroepithelium
cvTermList.description: Cells of epithelial origin possessing specialized sensory functions. They include cells that are found in the taste buds; olfactory mucosa; cochlea; and neuroepithelial bodies.

cvTermList.name: Neuron
cvTermList.description: The basic cellular units of nervous tissue. Each neuron consists of a body, an axon, and dendrites. Their purpose is to receive, conduct, and transmit impulses in the nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Neuroretina
cvTermList.description: The inner layer of the retina that contains the photoreceptors.

cvTermList.name: Neutrophil
cvTermList.description: Granular leukocytes having a nucleus with three to five lobes connected by slender threads of chromatin, and cytoplasm containing fine inconspicuous granules and stainable by neutral dyes.

cvTermList.name: Notochord
cvTermList.description: A cartilaginous rod of mesodermal cells at the dorsal midline of all chordate embryos. In lower vertebrates, notochord is the backbone of support. In the higher vertebrates, notochord is a transient structure, and segments of the vertebral column will develop around it. Notochord is also a source of midline signals that pattern surrounding tissues including the neural tube development.

cvTermList.name: Occipital lobe
cvTermList.description: Posterior part of the cerebral hemisphere.

cvTermList.name: Ocular ciliary body
cvTermList.description: A ring of tissue extending from the scleral spur to the ora serrata of the retina. It consists of the uveal portion and the epithelial portion. The ciliary muscle is in the uveal portion and the ciliary processes are in the epithelial portion.

cvTermList.name: Ocular ciliary epithelium
cvTermList.description: The ciliary epithelium is a double layer of columnar epithelial cells. The layer that has its basal lamina facing the posterior chamber is non-pigmented, and the one that has its basal lamina facing the connective tissue stroma of the ciliary body is pigmented and is directly continuous with the pigmented epithelial layer of the retina.

cvTermList.name: Odontoblast
cvTermList.description: A cell derived from a preodontoblast that secretes predentin. Each odontoblast has a cytoplasmic extension, an odontoblastic process that traverses the thickness of the dentin and helps to maintain the dentin.

cvTermList.name: Esophageal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the oesophagus. Non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium. In humans, the surface cells may exhibit some keratohyalin granules, but keratinization does not normally occur.

cvTermList.name: Esophageal squamous cell
cvTermList.description: A flat, scale-like epithelial cell that lines the upper and middle third of the esophageal lumen.

cvTermList.name: Esophagus
cvTermList.description: The muscular membranous segment between the pharynx and the stomach in the upper gastrointestinal tract.

cvTermList.name: Olfactory bulb
cvTermList.description: Ovoid body resting on the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone where the olfactory nerve terminates. The olfactory bulb contains several types of nerve cells including the mitral cells, on whose dendrites the olfactory nerve synapses, forming the olfactory glomeruli. The accessory olfactory bulb, which receives the projection from the vomeronasal organ via the vomeronasal nerve, is also included here.

cvTermList.name: Olfactory epithelium
cvTermList.description: An epithelium located in the roof, superior conchae, and septum of the nasal cavity. It is formed by ciliated olfactory receptor cells, supporting cells and basal cells. Olfactory glands in the epithelium produce and secrete mucus which forms a layer over the epithelium. The cilia of the receptor cells protrude into the mucous layer where molecular reception with odors occurs and sensory transduction begins. Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Oligodendrocyte
cvTermList.description: A class of large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system. Oligodendroglia may be called interfascicular, perivascular, or perineuronal (not the same as satellite cells, perineuronal of ganglia) according to their location. They form the insulating myelin sheath of axons in the central nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Oocyte
cvTermList.description: Female germ cells derived from oogonia and termed oocytes when they enter meiosis. The primary oocytes begin meiosis but are arrested at the diplotene state until ovulation at puberty to give rise to haploid secondary oocytes or ova (ovum).

cvTermList.name: Optic nerve
cvTermList.description: The 2nd cranial nerve. The optic nerve conveys visual information from the retina to the brain. The nerve carries the axons of the retinal ganglion cells which sort at the optic chiasm and continue via the optic tracts to the brain. The largest projection is to the lateral geniculate nuclei; other important targets include the superior colliculi and the suprachiasmatic nuclei. Though known as the second cranial nerve, it is considered part of the central nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Oral epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the oral cavity. The oral cavity is lined by masticatory mucosa, lining mucosa and specialized mucosa. The masticatory mucosa and lining mucosa have a keratinized or parakeratinized stratified squamous epithelium. The specialized mucosa is restricted to the dorsal surface of the tongue, where it contains papillae and taste buds.

cvTermList.name: Oral mucosa squamous cell
cvTermList.description: Squamous cell of oral epithelium.
synonyms: Oral cavity mucosa squamous epithelial cell

cvTermList.name: Oral mucosa
cvTermList.description: Lining of the oral cavity, including mucosa on the gums; the palate; the lip; the cheek; floor of the mouth; and other structures. The mucosa is generally a non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium covering muscle, bone, or glands but can show varying degree of keratinization at specific locations.

cvTermList.name: Organ of Corti
cvTermList.description: The spiral epithelium containing sensory auditory hair cells and supporting cells in the cochlea. Organ of Corti, situated on the basilar membrane and overlaid by a gelatinous tectorial membrane, converts sound-induced mechanical waves to neural impulses to the brain.

cvTermList.name: Oropharynx
cvTermList.description: The middle portion of the pharynx that lies posterior to the mouth, inferior to the soft palate, and superior to the base of the tongue and epiglottis. It has a digestive function as food passes from the mouth into the oropharynx before entering esophagus.

cvTermList.name: Osteoblast
cvTermList.description: Bone-forming cells which secrete an extracellular matrix. Hydroxyapatite crystals are then deposited into the matrix to form bone.

cvTermList.name: Osteoclast
cvTermList.description: A large multinuclear cell associated with the bone resorption. An odontoclast, also called cementoclast, is cytomorphologically the same as an osteoclast and is involved in cementum resorption.

cvTermList.name: Osteocyte
cvTermList.description: Mature osteoblasts that have become embedded in the bone matrix. They occupy a small cavity, called lacuna, in the matrix and are connected to adjacent osteocytes via protoplasmic projections called canaliculi.

cvTermList.name: Ovarian follicle
cvTermList.description: An oocyte-containing structure in the cortex of the ovary. The oocyte is enclosed by a layer of granulosa cells providing a nourishing microenvironment (follicular fluid). The number and size of follicles vary depending on the age and reproductive state of the female. The growing follicles are divided into five stages: primary, secondary, tertiary, Graafian, and atretic. Follicular growth and steroidogenesis depend on the presence of gonadotropins.

cvTermList.name: Ovarian follicular fluid
cvTermList.description: The fluid surrounding the ovum and granulosa cells in the Graafian follicle (ovarian follicle). The follicular fluid contains sex steroids, glycoprotein hormones, plasma proteins, mucopolysaccharides, and enzymes.

cvTermList.name: Ovarian granulosa cell
cvTermList.description: Supporting cells for the developing female gamete in the ovary. They are derived from the coelomic epithelial cells of the gonadal ridge. Granulosa cells form a single layer around the oocyte in the primordial ovarian follicle and advance to form a multilayered cumulus oophorus surrounding the ovum in the Graafian follicle. The major functions of granulosa cells include the production of steroids and LH receptors.

cvTermList.name: Ovarian stroma
cvTermList.description: The stroma of the ovary contains loose connective tissue, fibroblast, theca cells, a mass of relatively large contorted blood vessels, lymphatic vessels, and nerves.

cvTermList.name: Ovary
cvTermList.description: The reproductive organ (gonads) in female animals. In vertebrates, the ovary contains two functional parts: the ovarian follicle for the production of female germ cells (oogenesis); and the endocrine cells (granulosa cells; theca cells; and luteal cells) for the production of estrogens and progesterone.

cvTermList.name: Oviduct glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of oviduct epithelium. Example: peg cells, ciliated cells.

cvTermList.name: Oviduct
cvTermList.description: A pair of highly specialized muscular canals extending from the uterus to its corresponding ovary. They provide the means for ovum collection, and the site for the final maturation of gametes and fertilization. The fallopian tube consists of an interstitium, an isthmus, an ampulla, an infundibulum, and fimbriae. Its wall consists of three histologic layers: serous, muscular, and an internal mucosal layer lined with both ciliated and secretory cells.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral nervous system
cvTermList.description: The nervous system outside of the brain and spinal cord. The peripheral nervous system has autonomic and somatic divisions. The autonomic nervous system includes the enteric, parasympathetic, and sympathetic subdivisions. The somatic nervous system includes the cranial and spinal nerves and their ganglia and the peripheral sensory receptors.

cvTermList.name: Pancreas exocrine glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of exocrine pancreas epithelium. Example: pancreatic acinar cell, glandular cells in pancreatic canaliculi, glandular cells in pancreatic ducts.

cvTermList.name: Pancreas
cvTermList.description: A nodular organ in the abdomen that contains a mixture of endocrine glands and exocrine glands. The small endocrine portion consists of the islets of langerhans secreting a number of hormones into the blood stream. The large exocrine portion (exocrine pancreas) is a compound acinar gland that secretes several digestive enzymes into the pancreatic ductal system that empties into the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Pancreatic acinar cell
cvTermList.description: Acinar cells of the exocrine pancreas. They secrete digestive enzymes via a system of ducts.

cvTermList.name: Pancreatic islet
cvTermList.description: Irregular microscopic structures consisting of cords of endocrine cells that are scattered throughout the pancreas among the exocrine acini. Each islet is surrounded by connective tissue fibers and penetrated by a network of capillaries. There are four major cell types. The most abundant beta cells (50-80%) secrete insulin. Alpha cells (5-20%) secrete glucagon. PP cells (10-35%) secrete pancreatic polypeptide. Delta cells (~5%) secrete somatostatin.

cvTermList.name: Parathyroid glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of parathyroid epithelium. Example: Parathyroid chief cell and parathyroid oxyphil cells.

cvTermList.name: Parathyroid
cvTermList.description: Two pairs of small oval-shaped glands located in the front and the base of the neck and adjacent to the two lobes of thyroid gland. They secrete parathyroid hormone that regulates the balance of calcium; phosphorus; and magnesium in the body.

cvTermList.name: Parietal lobe
cvTermList.description: Upper central part of the cerebral hemisphere.

cvTermList.name: Parotid gland
cvTermList.description: The largest of the three pairs of salivary glands. They lie on the sides of the face immediately below and in front of the ear.

cvTermList.name: Pectoralis muscle
cvTermList.description: The pectoralis major and pectoralis minor muscles that make up the upper and fore part of the chest in front of the axilla.

cvTermList.name: Penis
cvTermList.description: The external reproductive organ of males. It is composed of a mass of erectile tissue enclosed in three cylindrical fibrous compartments. Two of the three compartments, the corpus cavernosa, are placed side-by-side along the upper part of the organ. The third compartment below, the corpus spongiosum, houses the urethra.
