cvTermList.name: Pericardium
cvTermList.description: A conical fibro-serous sac surrounding the heart and the roots of the great vessels (aorta; venae cavae; pulmonary artery). Pericardium consists of two sacs, the outer fibrous pericardium and the inner serous pericardium. The latter consists of an outer parietal layer facing the fibrous pericardium, and an inner visceral layer (epicardium) resting next to the heart, and a pericardial cavity between these two layers.

cvTermList.name: Periodontal ligament
cvTermList.description: The fibrous connective tissue surrounding the tooth root, separating it from and attaching it to the alveolar bone (alveolar process).

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood T-cell
cvTermList.description: T-cells found in peripheral blood.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood granulocyte
cvTermList.description: Granulocytes found in peripheral blood.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood leukocyte
cvTermList.description: Leukocytes found in peripheral blood.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood lymphocyte
cvTermList.description: Lymphocytes found in peripheral blood.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood monocyte
cvTermList.description: Monocytes found in peripheral blood.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood neutrophil
cvTermList.description: Neutrophils found in peripheral blood.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood cell
cvTermList.description: Peripheral blood cells are the cellular components of blood, consisting of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets, which are found within the circulating pool of blood and not sequestered within the lymphatic system, spleen, liver, or bone marrow.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral nerve
cvTermList.description: The nerves outside of the brain and spinal cord, including the autonomic, cranial, and spinal nerves. Peripheral nerves contain non-neuronal cells and connective tissue as well as axons. The connective tissue layers include, from the outside to the inside, the epineurium, the perineurium, and the endoneurium.

cvTermList.name: Peyer patch
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid tissue on the mucosa of the small intestine.
synonyms: Aggregated lymphoid nodules of small intestine

cvTermList.name: Pharynx
cvTermList.description: A funnel-shaped fibromuscular tube that conducts food to the esophagus, and air to the larynx and lungs. It is located posterior to the nasal cavity; oral cavity; and larynx, and extends from the skull base to the inferior border of the cricoid cartilage anteriorly and to the inferior border of the C6 vertebra posteriorly. It is divided into the nasopharynx; oropharynx; and hypopharynx (laryngopharynx).

cvTermList.name: Pineal gland
cvTermList.description: A light-sensitive neuroendocrine organ attached to the roof of the third ventricle of the brain. The pineal gland secretes melatonin, other biogenic amines, and neuropeptides.

cvTermList.name: Pituitary anterior lobe
cvTermList.description: The anterior glandular lobe of the pituitary gland, also known as the adenohypophysis. It secretes the adenohypophyseal hormones that regulate vital functions such as growth; metabolism; and reproduction.

cvTermList.name: Pituitary neurointermediate lobe
cvTermList.description: The intermediate lobe of the pituitary gland. It shows considerable size variation among the species, small in humans, and large in amphibians and lower vertebrates. This lobe produces mainly melanocyte-stimulating hormones and other peptides from post-translational processing of pro-opiomelanocortin (pomc).

cvTermList.name: Pituitary gland
cvTermList.description: A small, unpaired gland situated in the sella turcica. It is connected to the hypothalamus by a short stalk.

cvTermList.name: Placenta
cvTermList.description: A highly vascularized mammalian fetal-maternal organ and major site of transport of oxygen, nutrients, and fetal waste products. It includes a fetal portion (chorionic villi) derived from trophoblasts and a maternal portion (decidua) derived from the uterine endometrium. The placenta produces an array of steroid, protein and peptide hormones (placental hormones).

cvTermList.name: Plasma
cvTermList.description: The residual portion of blood that is left after removal of blood cells by centrifugation without prior blood coagulation.

cvTermList.name: Plasmacytoid dendritic cell
cvTermList.description: Plasmacytoid dendritic cells represent a distinct immune cell type specialized in direct virus recognition and rapid secretion of type I interferon.

cvTermList.name: Platelet
cvTermList.description: Non-nucleated disk-shaped cells formed in the megakaryocyte and found in the blood of all mammals. They are mainly involved in blood coagulation.

cvTermList.name: Pons
cvTermList.description: The front part of hindbrain that lies between medulla oblongata and the midbrain (mesencephalon) ventral to the cerebellum. It is composed of two parts, the dorsal and the ventral. Pons serves as a relay station for important neural pathways between the cerebellum to the cerebrum.

cvTermList.name: Portal vein
cvTermList.description: A short thick vein formed by union of the superior mesenteric vein and the splenic vein.

cvTermList.name: Posterior pituitary
cvTermList.description: Neural tissue of the pituitary gland, also known as the neurohypophysis. It consists of the distal axons of neurons that produce vasopressin and oxytocin in the supraoptic nucleus and the paraventricular nucleus. These axons travel down through the median eminence, the hypothalamic infundibulum of the pituitary stalk, to the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland.

cvTermList.name: Pre-B cell
cvTermList.description: Cells from the stage of B lymphocyte development where B cell heavy chain gene rearrangement is completed. The pre-B cell stage is preceded by the pro-B cell stage.

cvTermList.name: Preoptic area of hypothalamus
cvTermList.description: Region of hypothalamus between the anterior commissure and optic chiasm.

cvTermList.name: Preputial gland
cvTermList.description: Exocrine glands located at the anterior aspect of the genitals of some mammals that produce and secrete pheromones.

cvTermList.name: Promyelocyte
cvTermList.description: A promyelocyte (or progranulocyte) is a granulocyte precursor, developing from the myeloblast and developing into the myelocyte.

cvTermList.name: Prostate glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of prostate epithelium. A secretory cell that produces and secretes prostatic fluid. Prostatic fluid contains citric acid, the enzyme fibrinolysin that liquefies the semen, acid phosphatase, a number of other enzymes and lipids. The secretion of the prostate is the first fraction of the ejaculate.

cvTermList.name: Prostate
cvTermList.description: A gland in males that surrounds the neck of the urinary bladder and the urethra. It secretes a substance that liquefies coagulated semen. It is situated in the pelvic cavity behind the lower part of the pubic symphysis, above the deep layer of the triangular ligament, and rests upon the rectum.

cvTermList.name: Pulmonary artery
cvTermList.description: The short wide vessel arising from the conus arteriosus of the right ventricle and conveying unaerated blood to the lungs.

cvTermList.name: Pulmonary vein
cvTermList.description: The veins that return the oxygenated blood from the lungs to the left atrium of the heart.

cvTermList.name: Purkinje cell
cvTermList.description: The output neurons of the cerebellar cortex.

cvTermList.name: Rectum glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of rectal epithelium. Example: Goblet cell; enterocytes or absorptive cells; enteroendocrine and M cells.

cvTermList.name: Rectum
cvTermList.description: The distal segment of the large intestine, between the sigmoid colon and the anal canal.

cvTermList.name: Renal collecting duct
cvTermList.description: Straight tubes commencing in the radiate part of the kidney cortex where they receive the curved ends of the distal convoluted tubules. In the medulla the collecting tubules of each pyramid converge to join a central tube (duct of Bellini) which opens on the summit of the papilla.

cvTermList.name: Renal glomerulus
cvTermList.description: A cluster of convoluted capillaries beginning at each nephric tubule in the kidney and held together by connective tissue.

cvTermList.name: Kidney medulla
cvTermList.description: The internal portion of the kidney, consisting of striated conical masses, the renal pyramids, whose bases are adjacent to the cortex and whose apices form prominent papillae projecting into the lumen of the minor calyces.

cvTermList.name: Reticulocyte
cvTermList.description: Immature erythrocytes. In humans, these are erythroid cells that have just undergone extrusion of their cell nucleus. They still contain some organelles that gradually decrease in number as the cells mature. Ribosomes are last to disappear. Certain staining techniques cause components of the ribosomes to precipitate into characteristic reticulum (not the same as the endoplasmic reticulum), hence the name reticulocytes.

cvTermList.name: Retina
cvTermList.description: The ten-layered nervous tissue membrane of the eye. It is continuous with the optic nerve and receives images of external objects and transmits visual impulses to the brain. Its outer surface is in contact with the choroid and the inner surface with the vitreous body. The outermost layer is pigmented, whereas the inner nine layers are transparent.

cvTermList.name: Retinal cone cell
cvTermList.description: Photosensitive afferent neurons located primarily within the fovea centralis of the macula lutea. There are three major types of cone cells (red, blue, and green) with photopigments of different spectral sensitivity curves. Retinal cone cells operate in daylight vision (at photopic intensities) providing color recognition and central visual acuity.

cvTermList.name: Retinal ganglion
cvTermList.description: Neurons of the innermost layer of the retina, the internal plexiform layer. They are of variable sizes and shapes, and their axons project via the optic nerve to the brain. A small subset of these cells act as photoreceptors with projections to the suprachiasmatic nucleus, the center for regulating circadian rhythm.

cvTermList.name: Retinal photoreceptor
cvTermList.description: Specialized phototransduction neurons in the vertebrates, such as the retinal rod cells and the retinal cone cells. Non-visual photoreceptor neurons have been reported in the deep brain, the pineal gland and organs of the circadian system.

cvTermList.name: Retinal pigment epithelium
cvTermList.description: The single layer of pigment-containing epithelial cells in the retina, situated closely to the tips (outer segments) of the retinal photoreceptor cells. These epithelial cells perform essential functions for the photoreceptor cells, such as in nutrient transport, phagocytosis of the shed photoreceptor membranes, and ensuring retinal attachment.

cvTermList.name: Retinal rod cell
cvTermList.description: Photosensitive afferent neurons located in the peripheral retina, with density increases radially away from the fovea centralis. Being much more sensitive to light than the retinal cone cells, the rod cells are responsible for twilight vision (at scotopic intensities) as well as peripheral vision, but provide no color discrimination.

cvTermList.name: Saliva
cvTermList.description: The clear, viscous fluid secreted by the salivary glands and mucous glands of the mouth. It contains mucins, water, organic salts, and ptylin.

cvTermList.name: Salivary gland glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of salivary gland. Example: Serous cells, mucous cells, cuboidal epithelial cells of the intercalated ducts, simple cuboidal epithelium of the striated ducts, epithelial cells of excretory ducts.

cvTermList.name: Salivary gland
cvTermList.description: Glands that secrete saliva in the mouth. There are three pairs of salivary glands (parotid gland; sublingual gland; submandibular gland).

cvTermList.name: Saphenous vein
cvTermList.description: The vein which drains the foot and leg.

cvTermList.name: Scalp
cvTermList.description: The outer covering of the calvaria. It is composed of several layers: skin; subcutaneous connective tissue; the occipitofrontal muscle which includes the tendinous galea aponeurotica; loose connective tissue; and the pericranium (the periosteum of the skull).

cvTermList.name: Scapula
cvTermList.description: The flat triangle-shaped bone that connects the humerus with the clavicle in the back of the shoulder.

cvTermList.name: Schwann cell
cvTermList.description: Neuroglial cells of the peripheral nervous system which form the insulating myelin sheaths of peripheral axons.

cvTermList.name: Sciatic nerve
cvTermList.description: A nerve which originates in the lumbar and sacral spinal cord (L4 to S3) and supplies motor and sensory innervation to the lower extremity. The sciatic nerve, which is the main continuation of the sacral plexus, is the largest nerve in the body. It has two major branches, the tibial nerve and the peroneal nerve.

cvTermList.name: Semen
cvTermList.description: The thick, yellowish-white, viscid fluid secretion of male reproductive organs discharged upon ejaculation. In addition to reproductive organ secretions, it contains spermatozoa and their nutrient plasma.

cvTermList.name: Seminal plasma
cvTermList.description: The fluid portion of the semen.

cvTermList.name: Seminal vesicle glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of seminal vesicle epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Seminal vesicle
cvTermList.description: A saclike, glandular diverticulum on each ductus deferens in male vertebrates. It is united with the excretory duct and serves for temporary storage of semen.

cvTermList.name: Seminiferous epithelium
cvTermList.description: The epithelium lining the seminiferous tubules composed of primary male germ cells (spermatogonia) and supporting sertoli cells. As spermatogenesis proceeds, the developing germ cells migrate toward the lumen.
synonyms: Epithelium of seminiferous tubule of testis

cvTermList.name: Seminiferous tubule
cvTermList.description: The convoluted tubules in the testis where sperm are produced (spermatogenesis) and conveyed to the rete testis. Seminiferous tubules are composed of developing germ cells and the supporting sertoli cells.

cvTermList.name: Sertoli cell
cvTermList.description: Supporting cells projecting inward from the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules. They surround and nourish the developing male germ cells and secrete androgen-binding protein and hormones such as anti-mullerian hormone. The tight junctions of Sertoli cells with the spermatogonia and spermatocytes provide a blood-testis barrier.

cvTermList.name: Serum
cvTermList.description: The blood plasma with the fibrinogens removed. Serum includes all proteins not used in blood clotting (coagulation) and all the electrolytes, antibodies, antigens, hormones, and any exogenous substances (e.g., drugs and microorganisms).

cvTermList.name: Skeletal muscle
cvTermList.description: A subtype of striated muscle, attached by tendons to the skeleton. Skeletal muscles are innervated and their movement can be consciously controlled. They are also called voluntary muscles.

cvTermList.name: Skin appendage
cvTermList.description: Skin appendages are derived from epidermal epithelium during development. They include: hair follicles, sebaceous glands, eccrine sweat glands and apocrine sweat glands, and their products hair, sebum, serus secretion and sweat.

cvTermList.name: Skin fibroblast
cvTermList.description: Fibroblast from skin.

cvTermList.name: Skin
cvTermList.description: The outer covering of the body that protects it from the environment. It is composed of the dermis and the epidermis.

cvTermList.name: Slow-twitch skeletal muscle
cvTermList.description: Skeletal muscle fibers characterized by their expression of the Type I myosin heavy chain isoforms which have low atpase activity and effect several other functional properties - shortening velocity, power output, rate of tension redevelopment.

cvTermList.name: Small intestine glandular cell
cvTermList.description: A glandular cell found in the epithelium of the small intestine. Example: Enterocytes, Goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells; Paneth cells; M cells; Somatostatin-secreting Cells (D-cells) .

cvTermList.name: Small intestine mucosa
cvTermList.description: The villi (finger-like and leaf-like projections of the mucosa) and intestinal glands (crypts of Lieberkuehn) along with the lamina propia and associated galt (gut-associated lymphoid tissue) and muscularis mucosa constitute the essential features of the small intestinal mucosa.

cvTermList.name: Small intestine
cvTermList.description: The portion of the gastrointestinal tract between the pylorus of the stomach and the ileocecal valve of the large intestine. It is divisible into three portions: the duodenum, the jejunum, and the ileum.

cvTermList.name: Smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: Unstriated and unstriped muscle, one of the muscles of the internal organs, blood vessels, hair follicles, etc. Contractile elements are elongated, usually spindle-shaped cells with centrally located nuclei. Smooth muscle fibers are bound together into sheets or bundles by reticular fibers and frequently elastic nets are also abundant.

cvTermList.name: Spermatozoon
cvTermList.description: Mature male germ cells derived from spermatids. As spermatids move toward the lumen of the seminiferous tubules, they undergo extensive structural changes including the loss of cytoplasm, condensation of chromatin into the sperm head, formation of the acrosome cap, the sperm midpiece and the sperm tail that provides motility.

cvTermList.name: Spermatid
cvTermList.description: Male germ cells derived from the haploid secondary spermatocytes. Without further division, round spermatids undergo structural changes and give rise to elongated spermatids and finally to spermatozoa.

cvTermList.name: Spermatocyte
cvTermList.description: Male germ cells derived from spermatogonia. The diploid primary spermatocytes undergo meiosis and give rise to the haploid secondary spermatocytes which in turn give rise to spermatids.

cvTermList.name: Spinal cord
cvTermList.description: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge.

cvTermList.name: Spinal ganglion
cvTermList.description: Sensory ganglia located on the dorsal spinal roots within the vertebral column. The spinal ganglion cells are pseudounipolar. The single primary branch bifurcates sending a peripheral process to carry sensory information from the periphery and a central branch which relays that information to the spinal cord or brain.

cvTermList.name: Spleen red pulp
cvTermList.description: Red pulp contains large numbers of red blood cells. The red pulp consists of splenic sinuses separated by the splenic cords or cords of Billroth. Splenic cords contains large numbers of erythrocytes, macrophages, lymphocytes, plama cells and granulocytes.

cvTermList.name: Spleen white pulp
cvTermList.description: The white pulp consists of a cylindrical mass of lymphocytes arranged about a central artery. This mass of lymphocytes constitutes the periarterial lymphatic sheath (pals). Lymphatic nodules, ussually containing germinal centers, occur along the length of the periarterial sheath. The periarterial lymphatic sheath is surrounded by less densely packed lymphocytes that constitute the marginal zone. Pals are rich in T-lymphocytes and lymphatic nodules in B-lymphocytes. Region of active immune response through humoral and cell-mediated pathways.

cvTermList.name: Spleen
cvTermList.description: An organ that is part of the hematopoietic and immune systems. It is composed of the white pulp and the red pulp and is surrounded by a capsule. It is located in the left hypochondriac region. Its functions include lymphocyte production, blood cell storage, and blood cell destruction.

cvTermList.name: Splenocyte
cvTermList.description: A vague term that usually refers to the phagocytic cells (macrophages) of the spleen.

cvTermList.name: Sputum
cvTermList.description: Material coughed up from the lungs and expectorated via the mouth. It contains mucus, cellular debris, and microorganisms. It may also contain blood or pus.

cvTermList.name: Squamous cell
cvTermList.description: Flat cells that look like fish scales under a microscope. These cells cover internal and external surfaces of the body.

cvTermList.name: Sternum
cvTermList.description: The long, flat bone connecting with the cartilages of the first seven ribs and the clavicle.

cvTermList.name: Stomach glandular cell
cvTermList.description: A cell found in the gastric mucosa that produces and secretes mucus, digestive enzymes and/or acids. Example: Mucous neck cells, gastric chief cells, parietal cells (oxyntic cells), enteroendocrine cells, Gastrin-secreting Cells, Somatostatin-secreting Cells (D-cells).

cvTermList.name: Stomach
cvTermList.description: An organ of digestion situated in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen between the termination of the esophagus and the beginning of the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Stratum corneum
cvTermList.description: Outer layer of the epidermis. Composed of keratinized cells. Those cells do not have nucleus, are flat and generally adherent to other cells without cell boundaries.

cvTermList.name: Stria vascularis
cvTermList.description: A layer of stratified epithelium forming the endolymphatic border of the cochlear duct at the lateral wall of the cochlea. Stria vascularis contains primarily three cell types (marginal, intermediate, and basal), and capillaries. The marginal cells directly facing the endolymph are important in producing ion gradients and endochoclear potential.

cvTermList.name: Subcommissural organ
cvTermList.description: An ependymal derivative located at the junction of the third ventricle and the cerebral aqueduct, secreting somatostatin.

cvTermList.name: Sublingual gland
cvTermList.description: A salivary gland located under the tongue in the floor of the oral cavity.

cvTermList.name: Submandibular gland
cvTermList.description: One of two salivary glands in the neck, located in the space bound by the two bellies of the digastric muscle and the angle of the mandible. It discharges through the submandibular duct. The secretory units are predominantly serous although a few mucous alveoli, some with serous demilunes, occur.

cvTermList.name: Substantia nigra
cvTermList.description: The black substance in the ventral midbrain or the nucleus of cells containing the black substance. These cells produce dopamine, an important neurotransmitter in regulation of the sensorimotor system and mood. The dark colored melanin is a by-product of dopamine synthesis.

cvTermList.name: Subthalamic nucleus
cvTermList.description: Lens-shaped structure on the inner aspect of the internal capsule. The subthalamic nucleus and pathways traversing this region are concerned with the integration of somatic motor function.

cvTermList.name: Suprachiasmatic nucleus
cvTermList.description: An ovoid densely packed collection of small cells of the anterior hypothalamus lying close to the midline in a shallow impression of the optic chiasm.

cvTermList.name: Sweat gland
cvTermList.description: Sweat-producing structures that are embedded in the dermis. Each gland consists of a single tube, a coiled body, and a superficial duct.

cvTermList.name: Sympathetic ganglion
cvTermList.description: Ganglia of the sympathetic nervous system including the paravertebral and the prevertebral ganglia. Among these are the sympathetic chain ganglia, the superior, middle, and inferior cervical ganglia, and the aorticorenal, celiac, and stellate ganglia.

cvTermList.name: Synovial cell
cvTermList.description: A fibroblast that lies between the cartilaginous fibers in the synovial membrane of joints. Cells of the synovial membrane. There are two types: A and B .

cvTermList.name: Synovial fluid
cvTermList.description: The clear, viscous fluid secreted by the synovial membrane. It contains mucin, albumin, fat, and mineral salts and serves to lubricate joints.

cvTermList.name: Synovium
cvTermList.description: The dense connective-tissue membrane that secretes synovial fluid and that lines the ligamentous surfaces of articular capsules, tendon sheaths where free movement is necessary, and bursae.

cvTermList.name: T lymphoblast
cvTermList.description: An immature T-lymphocyte, that has enlarged following stimulation by an antigen, has the capacity to recognize the stimulating antigen and is undergoing proliferation and differentiation either to eliminate the antigen or to a memory state in order to recognize the future appearance of the antigen.

cvTermList.name: T-cell
cvTermList.description: Lymphocytes responsible for cell-mediated immunity. Two types have been identified - cytotoxic (T-lymphocytes, cytotoxic) and helper T-lymphocytes (T-lymphocytes, helper-inducer). They are formed when lymphocytes circulate through the thymus gland and differentiate to thymocytes. When exposed to an antigen, they divide rapidly and produce large numbers of new T cells sensitized to that antigen.

cvTermList.name: Taste bud
cvTermList.description: Small sensory organs which contain gustatory receptor cells, basal cells, and supporting cells. Taste buds in humans are found in the epithelia of the tongue, palate, and pharynx. They are innervated by the chorda tympani nerve (a branch of the facial nerve) and the glossopharyngeal nerve.

cvTermList.name: Tear
cvTermList.description: The fluid secreted by the lacrimal glands. This fluid moistens the conjunctiva and cornea.

cvTermList.name: Telencephalon
cvTermList.description: Derived from telencephalon, cerebrum is composed of a right and a left hemisphere. Each contains an outer cerebral cortex and a subcortical basal ganglia. The cerebrum includes all parts within the skull except the medulla oblongata, the pons, and the cerebellum. Cerebral functions include sensorimotor, emotional, and intellectual activities. The anterior subdivision of the embryonic forebrain (prosencephalon) or the corresponding part of the adult forebrain that includes the cerebrum and associated structures.

cvTermList.name: Temporal lobe
cvTermList.description: Lower lateral part of the cerebral hemisphere.

cvTermList.name: Tendon
cvTermList.description: Fibrous bands or cords of connective tissue at the ends of skeletal muscle fibers that serve to attach the muscles to bones and other structures.

cvTermList.name: Term myometrium
cvTermList.description: Refers to a myometrium from pregnant women at term (37 completed weeks of gestation, either in labor or not in labor).

cvTermList.name: Term placenta
cvTermList.description: Refers to a placenta from pregnant women at term (37 completed weeks of gestation, either in labor or not in labor).

cvTermList.name: Testis
cvTermList.description: The male gonad containing two functional parts: the seminiferous tubules for the production and transport of male germ cells (spermatogenesis) and the interstitial compartment containing leydig cells that produce androgens.

cvTermList.name: Thalamus
cvTermList.description: Paired bodies containing mostly gray substance and forming part of the lateral wall of the third ventricle of the brain. The thalamus represents the major portion of the diencephalon and is commonly divided into cellular aggregates known as nuclear groups.

cvTermList.name: Thigh epidermis
cvTermList.description: Epidermis of thigh.

cvTermList.name: Thoracic muscle
cvTermList.description: Muscle organ which is a part of the thorax. Examples: external intercostal muscle and diaphragm.

cvTermList.name: Thorax
cvTermList.description: The upper part of the trunk between the neck and the abdomen. It contains the chief organs of the circulatory and respiratory systems.

cvTermList.name: Thymic epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium of thymus.

cvTermList.name: Thymocyte
cvTermList.description: A cell that develops in the thymus, seemingly from a stem cell of bone marrow and of fetal liver, and is the precursor of the thymus-derived lymphocyte (T lymphocyte) that effects cell-mediated (delayed type) sensitivity.

cvTermList.name: Thymus
cvTermList.description: A single, unpaired primary lymphoid organ situated in the mediastinum, extending superiorly into the neck to the lower edge of the thyroid gland and inferiorly to the fourth costal cartilage. It is necessary for normal development of immunologic function early in life. By puberty, it begins to involute and much of the tissue is replaced by fat.

cvTermList.name: Thyroid follicular cell
cvTermList.description: An epithelial cell lining the thyroid follicles.

cvTermList.name: Thyroid
cvTermList.description: A highly vascularized endocrine gland consisting of two lobes joined by a thin band of tissue with one lobe on each side of the trachea. It secretes thyroid hormones from the follicular cells and calcitonin from the parafollicular cells thereby regulating metabolism and calcium level in blood, respectively.

cvTermList.name: Tibia
cvTermList.description: The second longest bone of the skeleton. It is located on the medial side of the lower leg, articulating with the fibula laterally, the talus distally, and the femur proximally.

cvTermList.name: Tongue epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the tongue. Stratified squamous epithelium, keratinized in parts.

cvTermList.name: Tongue
cvTermList.description: The muscular organ located in the floor of the mouth and serving as the principal organ of taste and modification of the voice in speech.

cvTermList.name: Tonsil germinal center cell
cvTermList.description: The germinal center or reaction center is the activated center of a lymphoid follicle in secondary lymphoid tissue where B-lymphocytes are stimulated by antigens and helper T cells (T-lymphocytes, helper-inducer) to generate memory cells. Here, the germinal center of a tonsil.

cvTermList.name: Tonsil lymphoid cell
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid cell located in the tonsil.

cvTermList.name: Tonsil squamous cell
cvTermList.description: Squamous cell of tonsil epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Tonsil
cvTermList.description: The human palatine tonsils and the nasopharyngeal tonsil are lymphoepithelial tissues located in strategic areas of the oropharynx and nasopharynx, although most commonly the term tonsils refers to the palatine tonsils. A round-to-oval mass of lymphoid tissue embedded in the lateral wall of the pharynx. There is one on each side of the oropharynx in the fauces between the anterior and posterior pillars of the soft palate.

cvTermList.name: Tooth enamel
cvTermList.description: A hard thin translucent layer of calcified substance which envelops and protects the dentin of the crown of the tooth. It is the hardest substance in the body and is almost entirely composed of calcium salts. Under the microscope, it is composed of thin rods (enamel prisms) held together by cementing substance, and surrounded by an enamel sheath.

cvTermList.name: Tooth
cvTermList.description: One of a set of bone-like structures in the mouth used for biting and chewing.

cvTermList.name: Trabecular meshwork
cvTermList.description: A porelike structure surrounding the entire circumference of the anterior chamber through which aqueous humor circulates to the canal of Schlemm.

cvTermList.name: Trachea
cvTermList.description: The cartilaginous and membranous tube descending from the larynx and branching into the right and left main bronchi.

cvTermList.name: Tracheal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium with many Goblet cells, lining the lumen of the trachea; the basement membrane is thick.

cvTermList.name: Tracheobronchial epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining both the trachea and bronchus.

cvTermList.name: Trophoblast
cvTermList.description: Cells lining the outside of the blastocyst. After binding to the endometrium, trophoblasts develop into two distinct layers, an inner layer of mononuclear cytotrophoblasts and an outer layer of continuous multinuclear cytoplasm, the syncytiotrophoblasts, which form the early fetal-maternal interface (placenta).

cvTermList.name: Trunk
cvTermList.description: The body excluding the head and neck and limbs.

cvTermList.name: Umbilical artery
cvTermList.description: Specialized arterial vessels in the umbilical cord. They carry waste and deoxygenated blood from the fetus to the mother via the placenta. In humans, there are usually two umbilical arteries but sometimes one.

cvTermList.name: Umbilical cord blood
cvTermList.description: Blood of the fetus. Exchange of nutrients and waste between the fetal and maternal blood occurs via the placenta. The cord blood is blood contained in the umbilical vessels (umbilical cord) at the time of delivery.

cvTermList.name: Umbilical cord
cvTermList.description: The flexible rope-like structure that connects a developing fetus to the placenta in mammals. The cord contains blood vessels which carry oxygen and nutrients from the mother to the fetus and waste products away from the fetus.

cvTermList.name: Umbilical vein endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium lining the umbilical vein.

cvTermList.name: Umbilical vein
cvTermList.description: Venous vessels in the umbilical cord. They carry oxygenated, nutrient-rich blood from the mother to the fetus via the placenta. In humans, there is normally one umbilical vein.

cvTermList.name: Ureter
cvTermList.description: One of a pair of thick-walled tubes that transports urine from the kidney pelvis to the urinary bladder.

cvTermList.name: Urethra
cvTermList.description: A tube that transports urine from the urinary bladder to the outside of the body in both the sexes. It also has a reproductive function in the male by providing a passage for sperm.

cvTermList.name: Urinary bladder smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: Smooth muscle of urinary bladder.

cvTermList.name: Urinary bladder urothelium
cvTermList.description: Transitional epithelium lining the urinary bladder.

cvTermList.name: Urinary bladder
cvTermList.description: A musculomembranous sac along the urinary tract. Urine flows from the kidneys into the bladder via the ureters, and is held there until urination.

cvTermList.name: Urine
cvTermList.description: The fluid that is excreted by the kidneys. It is stored in the bladder and discharged through the urethra.

cvTermList.name: Urothelium
cvTermList.description: The epithelial lining of the urinary tract. Transitional epithelium of the urinary tract.

cvTermList.name: Uterine corpus glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of uterine corpus epithelium. The phenotype of glandular cells in uterine corpus depends on hormonal status (menstrual cycle, and pre/post menopausal status).

cvTermList.name: Uterine corpus
cvTermList.description: Part of the uterus which is the site of embryo implantation and fetal development.

cvTermList.name: Uterine ectocervix
cvTermList.description: The part of the uterine cervix that projects into the vagina. It is lined with stratified squamous epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Uterine endothelium
cvTermList.description: Endothelium found in uterine blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Uterus
cvTermList.description: The hollow thick-walled muscular organ in the female pelvis. It consists of the fundus (the body) which is the site of embryo implantation and fetal development. Beyond the isthmus at the perineal end of fundus, is cervix uteri (the neck) opening into vagina. Beyond the isthmi at the upper abdominal end of fundus, are the fallopian tubes.

cvTermList.name: Vagina squamous cell
cvTermList.description: Squamous cell of vaginal epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Vagina
cvTermList.description: The genital canal in the female, extending from the uterus to the vulva.

cvTermList.name: Vas deferens
cvTermList.description: The excretory duct of the testes that carries spermatozoa. It rises from the scrotum and joins the seminal vesicles to form the ejaculatory duct.

cvTermList.name: Vascular smooth muscle
cvTermList.description: The non-striated, involuntary muscle tissue of blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Vein
cvTermList.description: The vessels carrying blood away from the capillary beds.

cvTermList.name: Visual cortex
cvTermList.description: Area of the occipital lobe concerned with vision.

cvTermList.name: Vulva
cvTermList.description: The external genitalia of the female. It includes the clitoris, the labia, the vestibule, and its glands.

cvTermList.name: Vulva/Anal skin
cvTermList.description: Skin pertaining both to the vulva and anus.

cvTermList.name: Vulva/Anal squamous cell
cvTermList.description: Squamous cell of vulva/anal epithelium.

cvTermList.name: White adipose tissue
cvTermList.description: Fatty tissue composed of white adipocytes and generally found directly under the skin (subcutaneous fat) and around the internal organs (abdominal fat). It has less vascularization and less coloration than the brown fat. White fat provides heat insulation, mechanical cushion, and source of energy. Fat cells with light coloration and few mitochondria. They contain a scant ring of cytoplasm surrounding a single large lipid droplet or vacuole.

cvTermList.name: Yolk sac
cvTermList.description: The first of four extra-embryonic membranes to form during embryogenesis. In reptiles and birds, it arises from endoderm and mesoderm to incorporate the egg yolk into the digestive tract for nourishing the embryo. In placental mammals, its nutritional function is vestigial; however, it is the source of intestinal mucosa; blood cells; and germ cells. It is sometimes called the vitelline sac, which should not be confused with the vitelline membrane of the egg.

cvTermList.name: Alimentary system
cvTermList.description: A group of organs stretching from the mouth to the anus, serving to breakdown foods, assimilate nutrients, and eliminate waste. In humans, the digestive system includes the gastrointestinal tract and the accessory glands (liver; biliary tract; pancreas).

cvTermList.name: Body part
cvTermList.description: Anatomical areas of the body.

cvTermList.name: Anatomical system
cvTermList.description: A group of organs that work together to accomplish a common function.

cvTermList.name: Anus
cvTermList.description: The external outlet of the gastrointestinal tract.

cvTermList.name: Appendix epithelium
cvTermList.description: Part of the large intestine epithelium lining the appendix. Simple columnar epithelium, consisting of many goblet cells.

cvTermList.name: Appendix mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the large intestine mucosa lining the appendix.

cvTermList.name: Autonomic nervous system
cvTermList.description: The enteric, parasympathetic, and sympathetic nervous systems taken together. Generally speaking, the autonomic nervous system regulates the internal environment during both peaceful activity and physical or emotional stress. Autonomic activity is controlled and integrated by the central nervous system, especially the hypothalamus and the solitary nucleus, which receive information relayed from visceral afferents; these and related central and sensory structures are sometimes (but not here) considered to be part of the autonomic nervous system itself.

cvTermList.name: B Lymphoblast
cvTermList.description: A morphologically immature B-lymphocyte, once thought to represent an early stage in lymphocyte development but now known to be an activated lymphocyte that has been transformed in response to antigenic stimulation.

cvTermList.name: Bone cell
cvTermList.description: Cell type found in bone tissue.

cvTermList.name: Bone marrow hematopoietic cell
cvTermList.description: Hematopoietic cells resident in the bone marrow. Include: hematopoietic stem cells (lymphoid stem cells and myeloid stem cells) and the precursor cells for thrombocytes, erythrocytes, basophils, neutrophils, eosinophils, monocytes and lymphocytes.

cvTermList.name: Bone tissue
cvTermList.description: A specialized connective tissue that is the main constituent of the skeleton. The principle cellular component of bone is comprised of osteoblasts; osteocytes; and osteoclasts, while fibrillar collagens and hydroxyapatite crystals form the bone matrix.

cvTermList.name: Breast
cvTermList.description: In humans, one of the paired regions in the anterior portion of the thorax. The breasts consist of the mammary glands, the skin, the muscles, the adipose tissue, and the connective tissues.

cvTermList.name: Bronchiole
cvTermList.description: The small airways branching off the tertiary bronchi. Terminal bronchioles lead into several orders of respiratory bronchioles which in turn lead into alveolar ducts and then into pulmonary alveoli.

cvTermList.name: Bronchoalveolar system
cvTermList.description: Bronchus, bronchiole and alveolus consider together.

cvTermList.name: Capillary
cvTermList.description: The minute vessels that connect the arterioles and venules.

cvTermList.name: Cardiovascular system
cvTermList.description: The heart and the blood vessels by which blood is pumped and circulated through the body.

cvTermList.name: Fetal tissue
cvTermList.description: Tissue from fetus.

cvTermList.name: Extraembryonic tissue
cvTermList.description: Tissues outside the embryo involved in protection and nutrition, such as amnion, chorionic membrane, placenta, umbilical cord and yolk sac.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic rhombencephalon
cvTermList.description: The embryonic rhombencephalon can be subdivided in a variable number of transversal swellings called rhombomeres. Rhombomeres Rh7-Rh4 form the myelencephalon that will give the medulla oblongata. Rhombomeres Rh3-Rh1 form the metencephalon that will form the pons and the cerebellum.

cvTermList.name: Cell type
cvTermList.description: The fundamental, structural, and functional units or subunits of living organisms. They are composed of cytoplasm containing various organelles and a cell membrane boundary.

cvTermList.name: Cerebellar cortex
cvTermList.description: The superficial very tightly folded layer of gray matter of the cerebellum. The cerebellar cortex is divided into three layers: granular layer, Purkinje layer and molecular layer.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral hemisphere
cvTermList.description: One half of the cerebrum, the part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

cvTermList.name: Choroid
cvTermList.description: The thin, highly vascular membrane covering most of the posterior of the eye between the retina and sclera.

cvTermList.name: Colorectum
cvTermList.description: Having to do with the colon or the rectum.

cvTermList.name: Connective tissue
cvTermList.description: Tissue that supports and binds other tissues. It consists of connective tissue cells embedded in a large amount of extracellular matrix.

cvTermList.name: Connective tissue cell
cvTermList.description: A group of cells that includes fibroblasts, cartilage cells, adipocytes, smooth muscle cells, and bone cells.

cvTermList.name: Dermal system
cvTermList.description: The outer covering of the body composed of the skin and the skin appendages, which are the hair, the nails; and the sebaceous glands and the sweat glands and their ducts.

cvTermList.name: Dermis
cvTermList.description: A layer of vascularized connective tissue underneath the epidermis. The surface of the dermis contains innervated papillae. Embedded in or beneath the dermis are sweat glands; hair follicles; and sebaceous glands.

cvTermList.name: Descending colon
cvTermList.description: The segment of large intestine between transverse colon and the sigmoid colon.

cvTermList.name: Duodenal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Simple columnar epithelium lining the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Dura mater
cvTermList.description: The outermost of the three meninges, a fibrous membrane of connective tissue that covers the brain and the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic pharynx
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult pharynx.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic structure
cvTermList.description: The anatomical parts that make up an organism in the early stages of development.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic tissue
cvTermList.description: The three primary germinal layers (ectoderm; endoderm; and mesoderm) developed during gastrulation that provide tissues and body plan of a mature organism. They derive from two early layers, hypoblast and epiblast.

cvTermList.name: Endocardium
cvTermList.description: The innermost layer of the heart, comprised of endothelial cells.

cvTermList.name: Endocrine gland
cvTermList.description: Ductless glands that secrete hormones directly into the blood circulation. These hormones influence the metabolism and other functions of cells in the body.

cvTermList.name: Endocrine system
cvTermList.description: The system of glands that release their secretions (hormones) directly into the circulatory system. In addition to the endocrine glands, included are the chromaffin system and the neurosecretory systems. We consider as members of the endocrine system the specialized ductless glands, and we do not include here other organs that have secondary endocrine functions.

cvTermList.name: Endocrine pancreas
cvTermList.description: Part of pancreas with endocrine function performed by the islets of Langerhans.

cvTermList.name: Enteric nervous system
cvTermList.description: Two ganglionated neural plexuses in the gut wall which form one of the three major divisions of the autonomic nervous system. The enteric nervous system innervates the gastrointestinal tract, the pancreas, and the gallbladder. It contains sensory neurons, interneurons, and motor neurons. Thus the circuitry can autonomously sense the tension and the chemical environment in the gut and regulate blood vessel tone, motility, secretions, and fluid transport. The system is itself governed by the central nervous system and receives both parasympathetic and sympathetic innervation.

cvTermList.name: Epididymal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the epididymis. Pseudostratified columnar. Contains two cell types: tall columnar cells and basal cells. The columnar cells are tallest in the head of the epididymis and diminish in height as the tail is reached. The free surface of the cell possesses stereocilia.

cvTermList.name: Epithalamus
cvTermList.description: The dorsal posterior subdivision of the diencephalon. The epithalamus is generally considered to include the habenular nuclei (habenula) and associated fiber bundles, the pineal body, and the epithelial roof of the third ventricle. The anterior and posterior paraventricular nuclei of the thalamus are included with the thalamic nuclei although they develop from the same pronuclear mass as the epithalamic nuclei and are sometimes considered part of the epithalamus.

cvTermList.name: Epithelial cell
cvTermList.description: Cells that line the inner and outer surfaces of the body by forming cellular layers (epithelium) or masses. Epithelial cells lining the skin; the mouth; the nose; and the anal canal derive from ectoderm; those lining the respiratory system and the digestive system derive from endoderm; others (cardiovascular system and lymphatic system) from mesoderm.

cvTermList.name: Exocrine gland
cvTermList.description: A gland from which secretions reach a free surface of the body by ducts.

cvTermList.name: Exocrine pancreas epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the exocrine pancreas.

cvTermList.name: Exocrine system
cvTermList.description: The system of glands that release their secretions through ducts into the external environment.

cvTermList.name: Extraembryonic fluid
cvTermList.description: The amniotic fluid and the umbilical cord blood are considered here extraembryonic fluids.

cvTermList.name: Female reproductive system
cvTermList.description: The external and internal organs related to female reproduction. Includes the uterus, the ovaries, the fallopian tubes, the vagina and vulva.

cvTermList.name: Fetal bone
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult bone.

cvTermList.name: Fetal cochlea
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult cochlea.

cvTermList.name: Fetal dura mater
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult dura mater.

cvTermList.name: Fetal ear
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult ear.

cvTermList.name: Fetal frontal lobe
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult frontal lobe.

cvTermList.name: Fetal hippocampus
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult hippocampus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal hypothalamus
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult hypothalamus.

cvTermList.name: Fetal pituitary gland
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult pituitary gland.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic tongue
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult tongue.

cvTermList.name: First arch
cvTermList.description: The first branchial arch, also called the first pharyngeal arch and mandibular arch, is the first of six pharyngeal arches that develops in fetal life during the fourth week of development. It is located between the stomodeum and the first pharyngeal groove.

cvTermList.name: Fluid and secretion
cvTermList.description: Liquid substances produced by living organisms to fulfill specific functions or excreted as waste.

cvTermList.name: Fourth ventricle
cvTermList.description: An irregularly shaped cavity in the rhombencephalon, between the medulla oblongata, the pons, and the isthmus in front, and the cerebellum behind. It is continuous with the central canal of the cord below and with the cerebral aqueduct above, and through its lateral and median apertures it communicates with the subarachnoid space.

cvTermList.name: Fovea centralis
cvTermList.description: An area approximately 1.5 millimeters in diameter within the macula lutea where the retina thins out greatly because of the oblique shifting of all layers except the pigment epithelium layer. It includes the sloping walls of the fovea (clivus) and contains a few rods in its periphery. In its center (foveola) are the cones most adapted to yield high visual acuity, each cone being connected to only one ganglion cell.

cvTermList.name: Gall bladder epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the gall bladder. Tall simple columnar absorptive epithelium. Has characteristics that distinguish it from the absorptive epithelium of other organs such as the intestines. Only tall columnar cells are present in the epithelial layer. The nuclei are in the basal portion of the cell. The cells possess a thin apical striated border. The epithelial cells frequently exhibit distended intercellular spaces at their basal aspect.

cvTermList.name: Gestational structure
cvTermList.description: Any of the developmental structures during the gestation period (from fertilization to birth).

cvTermList.name: Gingiva
cvTermList.description: Oral tissue surrounding and attached to teeth.

cvTermList.name: Glandular cell
cvTermList.description: An epithelial cell which may release secretions to a free epithelial surface (exocrine) or to the circulatory system (endocrine). Glandular cells are part of glandular epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Globus pallidus
cvTermList.description: The representation of the phylogenetically oldest part of the corpus striatum called the paleostriatum. It forms the smaller, more medial part of the lentiform nucleus.

cvTermList.name: Greater omentum
cvTermList.description: A large fold of peritoneum that hangs down from the stomach, and extends from the stomach to the posterior abdominal wall after associating with the transverse colon.

cvTermList.name: Hematopoietic cell
cvTermList.description: A cell of a hematopoietic lineage.

cvTermList.name: Hemolymphoid and immune system
cvTermList.description: The hematopoietic, lymphoid and immune systems considered together. The immune system is the body's defense mechanism against foreign organisms or substances and deviant native cells. It includes the humoral immune response and the cell-mediated response and consists of a complex of interrelated cellular, molecular, and genetic components.

cvTermList.name: Histiocyte
cvTermList.description: Macrophages found in the tissues, as opposed to those found in the blood (monocytes) or serous cavities (serous membrane).

cvTermList.name: Hypopharynx
cvTermList.description: The bottom portion of the pharynx situated below the oropharynx and posterior to the larynx. The hypopharynx communicates with the larynx through the laryngeal inlet, and is also called laryngopharynx.

cvTermList.name: Joint
cvTermList.description: The connection point between two bones or skeletal elements. The joint may be fixed or movable. Is an organ that constitutes an anatomical junction; it consists of two or more adjacent bones, parts of which are interconnected by organ parts that consist of various types of connective tissue. Together with other joints and bones, a joint constitutes the skeletal system. Example(s): pubic symphysis, knee joint, temporomandibular joint.

cvTermList.name: Large intestine
cvTermList.description: A segment of the lower gastrointestinal tract that includes the cecum; the colon; and the rectum.

cvTermList.name: Large intestine epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the large intestine. The mucosal epithelium of the large intestine contains the same cell types as the small intestine (enterocytes or absorptive cells, goblet, paneth, enteroendocrine and M cells) but paneth cells are normally absent in the adult human.

cvTermList.name: Large intestine mucosa
cvTermList.description: The mucosa of the large intestine contains numerous straight tubular glands (crypts of Lieberkuehn) that extend through the full thickness of the mucosa. The glands consist of simple cuboidal epithelium, as does the intestinal surface from which they invaginate.

cvTermList.name: Lateral thalamic nuclei
cvTermList.description: A narrow strip of cell groups on the dorsomedial surface of the thalamus. It includes the lateral dorsal nucleus, lateral posterior nucleus, and the pulvinar.

cvTermList.name: Limbic lobe
cvTermList.description: The limbic lobe is an arc-shaped region of cortex on the medial surface of each cerebral hemisphere of the mammalian brain, consisting of parts of the frontal, parietal and temporal lobes. A horseshoe-shaped section of the cerebral cortex, comprising the cingulate gyrus and the parahippocampal gyrus.

cvTermList.name: Limbic system
cvTermList.description: A set of forebrain structures common to all mammals that is defined functionally and anatomically. It is implicated in the higher integration of visceral, olfactory, and somatic information as well as homeostatic responses including fundamental survival behaviors (feeding, mating, emotion). For most authors, it includes the amygdala; epithalamus; gyrus cinguli; hippocampal formation (see hippocampus); hypothalamus; parahippocampal gyrus; septal nuclei; anterior nuclear group of thalamus, and portions of the basal ganglia.

cvTermList.name: Liver and biliary system
cvTermList.description: The liver, bile ducts and gallbladder consider together.

cvTermList.name: Lymphatic system
cvTermList.description: A system of organs and tissues that process and transport immune cells and lymph.

cvTermList.name: Lymphatic vessel
cvTermList.description: Tubular vessels that are involved in the transport of lymph and lymphocytes.

cvTermList.name: Lymphoid stem cell
cvTermList.description: Stem cells from which B-lymphocytes, T-lymphocytes, natural killer cells, and some dendritic cells derive.

cvTermList.name: Macroglia
cvTermList.description: The astrocytes and oligodendrocytes considered together.

cvTermList.name: Male reproductive system
cvTermList.description: The external and internal organs related to male reproduction. Includes the testes, the epididymis, the ejaculatory fluid producing glands (seminal vesicles, prostate, and vas deferens), the penis, the urethra, and Cowper's gland.

cvTermList.name: Metencephalon
cvTermList.description: The anterior portion of the developing hindbrain. It gives rise to the cerebellum and the pons.

cvTermList.name: Mucosa
cvTermList.description: An epithelium with mucus-secreting cells, such as goblet cells. It forms the lining of many body cavities, such as the digestive tract, the respiratory tract, and the reproductive tract. Mucosa, rich in blood and lymph vessels, comprises an inner epithelium, a middle layer (lamina propria) of loose connective tissue, and an outer layer (muscularis mucosae) of smooth muscle cells that separates the mucosa from submucosa.

cvTermList.name: Muscle cell
cvTermList.description: Mature contractile cells, commonly known as myocytes, that form one of three kinds of muscle. The three types of muscle cells are skeletal (muscle fibers, skeletal), cardiac (myocytes, cardiac), and smooth (myocytes, smooth muscle). They are derived from embryonic (precursor) muscle cells called myoblasts.

cvTermList.name: Musculoskeletal system
cvTermList.description: The muscles, bones (bone and bones), and cartilage of the body.

cvTermList.name: Myeloid stem cell
cvTermList.description: Stem cells derived from hematopoietic stem cells. Derived from these myeloid progenitor cells are the megakaryocytes; erythroid cells; myeloid cells; and some dendritic cells.

cvTermList.name: Nail
cvTermList.description: The thin, horny plates that cover the dorsal surfaces of the distal phalanges of the fingers and toes of primates.

cvTermList.name: Neck
cvTermList.description: The region that connects the head to the rest of the body.

cvTermList.name: Nephron
cvTermList.description: The functional units of the kidney, consisting of the glomerulus and the attached tubule.

cvTermList.name: Nervous system
cvTermList.description: The entire nerve apparatus, composed of a central part, the brain and spinal cord, and a peripheral part, the cranial and spinal nerves, autonomic ganglia, and plexuses.

cvTermList.name: Nervous system cell
cvTermList.description: Cell types pertaining to the nevous system.

cvTermList.name: Nose
cvTermList.description: A part of the upper respiratory tract. It contains the organ of smell. The term includes the external nose, the nasal cavity, and the paranasal sinuses.

cvTermList.name: Omentum
cvTermList.description: A double-layered fold of peritoneum that attaches the stomach to other organs in the abdominal cavity. A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera.

cvTermList.name: Mouth
cvTermList.description: The oval-shaped oral cavity located at the apex of the digestive tract and consisting of two parts: the vestibule and the oral cavity proper.

cvTermList.name: Osseous labyrinth
cvTermList.description: The essential part of the hearing organ consists of two labyrinthine compartments: the bony labyrinthine and the membranous labyrinth. The bony labyrinth is a complex of three interconnecting cavities or spaces (cochlea; vestibular labyrinth; and semicircular canals) in the temporal bone. Within the bony labyrinth lies the membranous labyrinth which is a complex of sacs and tubules (cochlear duct; saccule and utricle; and semicircular ducts) forming a continuous space enclosed by epithelium and connective tissue. These spaces are filled with labyrinthine fluids of various compositions.

cvTermList.name: Oviduct epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the oviduct. Simple columnar epithelium composed of two kinds of cells, ciliated and non-ciliated. They represent different functional states of a single cell type. The epithelial cells undergo cyclic changings during menstrual cycle.

cvTermList.name: Parahippocampal gyrus
cvTermList.description: A gray matter cortical region of the brain that surrounds the hippocampus. This region plays an important role in memory encoding and retrieval.

cvTermList.name: Parasympathetic nervous system
cvTermList.description: The craniosacral division of the autonomic nervous system. The cell bodies of the parasympathetic preganglionic fibers are in brain stem nuclei and in the sacral spinal cord. They synapse in cranial autonomic ganglia or in terminal ganglia near target organs. The parasympathetic nervous system generally acts to conserve resources and restore homeostasis, often with effects reciprocal to the sympathetic nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Peritoneum
cvTermList.description: A membrane of squamous epithelial cells, the mesothelial cells, covered by apical microvilli that allow rapid absorption of fluid and particles in the peritoneal cavity. The peritoneum is divided into parietal and visceral components. The parietal peritoneum covers the inside of the abdominal wall. The visceral peritoneum covers the intraperitoneal organs. The double-layered peritoneum forms the mesentery that suspends these organs from the abdominal wall.

cvTermList.name: Pleura
cvTermList.description: The thin serous membrane enveloping the lungs (lung) and lining the thoracic cavity. Pleura consist of two layers, the inner visceral pleura lying next to the pulmonary parenchyma and the outer parietal pleura. Between the two layers is the pleural cavity which contains a thin film of liquid.

cvTermList.name: Prostate epithelium
cvTermList.description: The epithelium of the prostate is generally columnar but may have patches that are cuboidal, squamous, or pseudostratified.

cvTermList.name: Putamen
cvTermList.description: The largest and most lateral of the basal ganglia lying between the lateral medullary lamina of the globus pallidus and the external capsule. It is part of the neostriatum and forms part of the lentiform nucleus along with the globus pallidus.

cvTermList.name: Rectal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Simple columnar epithelium lining the rectum.

cvTermList.name: Rectum mucosa
cvTermList.description: Part of the large intestine mucosa lining the rectum.

cvTermList.name: Renal corpuscle
cvTermList.description: The renal corpuscle contains the filtration apparatus of the kidney. Are spherical structures composed of a glomerulus (glomerular vascular tuft) surrounded by the visceral and parietal epithelium of Bowman's capsule.

cvTermList.name: Reproductive system
cvTermList.description: The external and internal organs related to reproduction.

cvTermList.name: Respiratory system
cvTermList.description: The tubular and cavernous organs and structures, by means of which pulmonary ventilation and gas exchange between ambient air and the blood are brought about.

cvTermList.name: Salivary gland epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium of the salivary gland. It can be simple cuboidal, stratified cuboidal, stratified squamous, stratified columnar or pseudostratified.

cvTermList.name: Seminal vesicle epithelium
cvTermList.description: Pseudostratified columnar epithelium that contains tall, non-ciliated columnar cells and short round cells that rest on the basal lamina. The columnar cells have the morphology of protein-secreting cells.

cvTermList.name: Sense organ
cvTermList.description: Organ involved in the perception of internal and/or external stimuli.

cvTermList.name: Sigmoid colon
cvTermList.description: A segment of the colon between the rectum and the descending colon.

cvTermList.name: Paranasal sinuses
cvTermList.description: Air-filled spaces located within the bones around the nasal cavity. They are extensions of the nasal cavity and lined by the ciliated nasal mucosa. Each sinus is named for the cranial bone in which it is located, such as the ethmoid sinus; the frontal sinus; the maxillary sinus; and the sphenoid sinus.

cvTermList.name: Skeletal system
cvTermList.description: The framework that supports the soft tissues of vertebrate animals and protects many of their internal organs. The skeletons of vertebrates are made of bone and/or cartilage.

cvTermList.name: Small intestine epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the small intestine. The mature cells of the intestinal epithelium are found both in the crypts and on the surface of the villi. They include enterocytes or absorptive cells, goblet cells, paneth cells, enteroendocrine cells and M cells.

cvTermList.name: Stem cell
cvTermList.description: Relatively undifferentiated cells that retain the ability to divide and proliferate throughout postnatal life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

cvTermList.name: Stomach epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the stomach. Simple columnar epithelium. These columnar cells are designated surface mucous cells. Each cell possesses a large apical cup of mucinogen granules, thereby creating an epithelial surface that is a glandular sheet of cells. The mucus cup occupies most of the volume of the cell.

cvTermList.name: Striated muscle
cvTermList.description: One of two types of muscle in the body, characterized by the array of bands observed under microscope. Striated muscles can be divided into two subtypes: the cardiac muscle and the skeletal muscle.

cvTermList.name: Subthalamus
cvTermList.description: A transition zone in the anterior part of the diencephalon interposed between the thalamus, hypothalamus, and tegmentum of the mesencephalon. Components of the subthalamus include the subthalamic nucleus, zona incerta, nucleus of field H, and the nucleus of ansa lenticularis. The latter contains the entopeduncular nucleus.

cvTermList.name: Superior vestibular nuclei
cvTermList.description: The superior vestibular nucleus (Bechterews nucleus) is the dorso-lateral part of the vestibular nucleus and receives collaterals and terminals from the ascending branches of the vestibular nerve.

cvTermList.name: Sympathetic chain
cvTermList.description: A paired bundle of nerve fibers that run from the base of the skull to the coccyx.

cvTermList.name: Sympathetic nervous system
cvTermList.description: The thoracolumbar division of the autonomic nervous system. Sympathetic preganglionic fibers originate in neurons of the intermediolateral column of the spinal cord and project to the paravertebral and prevertebral ganglia, which in turn project to target organs. The sympathetic nervous system mediates the body's response to stressful situations, i.e., the fight or flight reactions. It often acts reciprocally to the parasympathetic system.

cvTermList.name: Thigh
cvTermList.description: A part of the lower limb, located between hip and knee.

cvTermList.name: Third ventricle
cvTermList.description: A narrow cleft inferior to the corpus callosum, within the diencephalon, between the paired thalami. Its floor is formed by the hypothalamus, its anterior wall by the lamina terminalis, and its roof by ependyma. It communicates with the fourth ventricle by the cerebral aqueduct, and with the lateral ventricles by the interventricular foramina.

cvTermList.name: Tissue
cvTermList.description: Collections of differentiated cells, such as epithelium; connective tissue; muscles; and nerve tissue. Tissues are cooperatively arranged to form organs with specialized functions such as respiration; digestion; reproduction; movement; and others.

cvTermList.name: Tonsil epithelium
cvTermList.description: The epithelium that forms the surface of the tonsil dips into the underlying connective tissue in numerous places, forming crypts kown as tonsillar crypts. Stratified squamous epithelium, that may be heavily infiltrated by lymphocytes. Epithelial cells are present in the germinal as well as in the periphery of the nodule.

cvTermList.name: Transverse colon
cvTermList.description: The segment of large intestine between ascending colon and descending colon. It passes from the right colic flexure across the abdomen, then turns sharply at the left colonic flexure into the descending colon.

cvTermList.name: Trigeminal nucleus
cvTermList.description: Nuclei of the trigeminal nerve situated in the brain stem. They include the nucleus of the spinal trigeminal tract (trigeminal nucleus, spinal), the principal sensory nucleus, the mesencephalic nucleus, and the motor nucleus.

cvTermList.name: Urinary system
cvTermList.description: The urinary system is the organ system that produces, stores, and eliminates urine. In humans it includes two kidneys, two ureters, the bladder, the urethra, and two sphincter muscles.

cvTermList.name: Vaginal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the vagina. Non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Ventricular system of brain
cvTermList.description: The ventricular system is a set of structures containing cerebrospinal fluid in the brain. The system comprises four ventricles: right and left lateral ventricles, third ventricle and fourth ventricle. It is continuous with the central canal of the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Vermis
cvTermList.description: A medial narrow structure connecting the two hemispheres of the cerebellum.

cvTermList.name: Vestibular nuclei
cvTermList.description: The four cellular masses in the floor of the fourth ventricle giving rise to a widely dispersed special sensory system. Included is the superior, medial, inferior, and lateral vestibular nucleus.

cvTermList.name: Vulva/Anal epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the vulva/anal region.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic thyroid
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult thyroid.

cvTermList.name: Fetal bone marrow
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult bone marrow.

cvTermList.name: Fetal ovary
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult ovary.

cvTermList.name: Fetal small intestine
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult small intestine.

cvTermList.name: Developmental tissue
cvTermList.description: Tissue from embryo or fetus.

cvTermList.name: Anal canal
cvTermList.description: The terminal segment of the large intestine, beginning from the ampulla of the rectum and ending at the anus.

cvTermList.name: Articular ligament
cvTermList.description: Fibrous tissue that connects bones to other bones.

cvTermList.name: Blood vessel vascular endothelium
cvTermList.description: Single pavement layer of cells which line the luminal surface of the blood vessels and regulate the transport of macromolecules and blood components from interstitium to lumen; this function has been most intensively studied in the blood capillaries.

cvTermList.name: Brain macroglia
cvTermList.description: Macroglia cells resident in the brain.

cvTermList.name: Brain microglia
cvTermList.description: Microglia cells resident in the brain.

cvTermList.name: Brain meninges
cvTermList.description: Meninges covering the brain.

cvTermList.name: Decidua menstrualis
cvTermList.description: The hormone-responsive glandular layer of endometrium that sloughs off at each menstrual flow (decidua menstrualis) or at the termination of pregnancy. During pregnancy, the thickest part of the decidua forms the maternal portion of the placenta, thus named decidua placentalis. The thin portion of the decidua covering the rest of the embryo is the decidua capsularis.

cvTermList.name: Dental cementum
cvTermList.description: The bonelike rigid connective tissue covering the root of a tooth from the cementoenamel junction to the apex and lining the apex of the root canal, also assisting in tooth support by serving as attachment structures for the periodontal ligament.

cvTermList.name: Hematopoietic tissue
cvTermList.description: Tissue in which new blood cells are formed.

cvTermList.name: Joint synovium
cvTermList.description: The inner membrane of a joint capsule surrounding a freely movable joint. It is loosely attached to the external fibrous capsule and secretes synovial fluid.

cvTermList.name: Ligament
cvTermList.description: Dense regular connective tissue connecting two or more adjacent skeletal elements or supporting an organ.

cvTermList.name: Lymphatic vessel vascular endothelium
cvTermList.description: Unbroken cellular lining (intima) of the lymph vessels (e.g., the high endothelial lymphatic venules). It is more permeable than blood vessel vascular endothelium, lacking selective absorption and functioning mainly to remove plasma proteins that have filtered through the capillaries into the tissue spaces.

cvTermList.name: Mucus
cvTermList.description: The viscous secretion of mucous membranes. It contains mucin, white blood cells, water, inorganic salts, and exfoliated cells.

cvTermList.name: Natural killer T cell
cvTermList.description: A specialized subset of T-lymphocytes that exhibit features of innate immunity similar to that of natural killer cells. They are reactive to glycolipids presented in the context of the major histocompatibility complex (mhc) class I-like molecule, CD1D antigen.

cvTermList.name: Optic disk
cvTermList.description: The portion of the optic nerve seen in the fundus with the ophthalmoscope. It is formed by the meeting of all the retinal ganglion cell axons as they enter the optic nerve.

cvTermList.name: Parathyroid epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium of parathyroid gland.

cvTermList.name: Parathyroid chief cell
cvTermList.description: The primary cell of the parathyroid gland. Its contains secretory granules, large Golgi complexes, and moderate numbers of mitochondria. It produces parathyroid hormone. The cells occur in sheets interspersed with areas of fatty tissue. Occasionally the cells are arranged in follicles.

cvTermList.name: Pneumocyte
cvTermList.description: Epithelial cells that line the pulmonary alveoli.

cvTermList.name: Semicircular canal
cvTermList.description: Three long canals (anterior, posterior, and lateral) of the bony labyrinth. They are set at right angles to each other and are situated posterosuperior to the vestibule of the bony labyrinth (vestibular labyrinth). The semicircular canals have five openings into the vestibule with one shared by the anterior and the posterior canals. Within the canals are the semicircular ducts.

cvTermList.name: Skeletal muscle cell
cvTermList.description: Large, multinucleate single cells, either cylindrical or prismatic in shape, that form the basic unit of skeletal muscle. They consist of myofibrils enclosed within and attached to the sarcolemma. They are derived from the fusion of skeletal myoblasts into a syncytium, followed by differentiation.

cvTermList.name: Smooth muscle cell
cvTermList.description: Non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cells found lining the digestive tract, uterus, and blood vessels. They are derived from specialized myoblasts (smooth muscle myoblasts).

cvTermList.name: Spinal cord macroglia
cvTermList.description: Macroglia cells resident in the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Spinal cord microglia
cvTermList.description: Microglia cells resident in the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Spinal cord meninges
cvTermList.description: Meninges covering the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Striated muscle cell
cvTermList.description: A cylindrical multinucleated cell containing contracting myofibrils, across which run transverse light and dark areas, enclosed in a delicate plasma membrane.

cvTermList.name: Tendon synovium
cvTermList.description: Synovium of tendon.

cvTermList.name: Thyroid epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium of thyroid gland.

cvTermList.name: Thyroid gland glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Glandular cell of thyroid. Example: thyroid follicular cell, parafollicular cells (also called C cells).

cvTermList.name: Uterine corpus epithelium
cvTermList.description: Epithelium lining the uterine corpus. The endometrium (mucosa of the uterus) is lined by a simple columnar epithelium with a mixture of secretory and ciliated cells.

cvTermList.name: Adrenal gland glandular cell
cvTermList.description: Hormone secreting cell located in the cortex of adrenal gland. Glandular cells in the adrenal cortex secrete mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids and androgens.

cvTermList.name: Human anatomical entity
cvTermList.description: Human anatomical entity

cvTermList.name: Lymph node nongerminal center cell
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid cells outside the reaction centra of lymph nodes.

cvTermList.name: Tonsil nongerminal center cell
cvTermList.description: Lymphoid cells outside the reaction centra of tonsil.

cvTermList.name: Vulva/Anal skin epidermal cell
cvTermList.description: Any of the epidermal cells found in the vulva/anal skin epidermis.

cvTermList.name: Ovum
cvTermList.description: A mature haploid female germ cell extruded from the ovary at ovulation.

cvTermList.name: Conventional dendritic cell
cvTermList.description: The dendritic cells (DC) subtypes present in the steady state, before infection, include type 1 interferon-producing plasmacytoid DCs (pDCs), migratory DCs such as Langerhans cells, and lymphoid tissue-resident conventional DCs (cDCs). The lymphoid tissue-resident cDCs consist of different subtypes, including CD8+ cDCs and CD8- cDCs2.

cvTermList.name: Spermatogonia
cvTermList.description: Diploid male germ cells of an early stage of spermatogenesis, derived from prespermatogonia. With the onset of puberty, spermatogonia at the basement membrane of the seminiferous tubule proliferate by mitotic division to produce two diploid intermediate cells called primary spermatocytes.

cvTermList.name: Primary spermatocyte
cvTermList.description: Diploid germ cell formed by mitosis of spermatogonia cell. The primary spermatocytes undergo first meiotic division giving rise to secondary spermatocytes.

cvTermList.name: Secondary spermatocyte
cvTermList.description: Haploid germ cell formed by first meiotic division of primary spermatocytes. The secondary spermatocyte undergo second meiotic division giving rise to spermatids.

cvTermList.name: Adluminal compartment of the seminiferous tubule
cvTermList.description: The inner two thirds of the seminiferous tubules that contain spermatocytes and the more advanced germ cells.

cvTermList.name: Olfactory mucosa
cvTermList.description: The part of the nasal mucosa composed of neuroepithelial tissue and mucus-producing Bowman's glands. The mucus moistens the epithelium and helps dissolve odor-containing gases.

cvTermList.name: Renal proximal convoluted tubule
cvTermList.description: The initial convoluted portion of the proximal tubule of the nephron. In relation to the morphology of the kidney as a whole, the convoluted segments of the proximal tubules are confined entirely to the renal cortex. Is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium with brushed borders which help to increase the area of absorption greatly.

cvTermList.name: Radius
cvTermList.description: The Radius is one of the two large bones of the forearm, the other being the ulna. It extends from the lateral side of the elbow to the thumb side of the wrist and runs parallel to the ulna, which exceeds it in length and size.
