It is a long bone, prism-shaped and slightly curved longitudinally. The radius articulates with the capitulum of the humerus, the radial notch and the head of the ulna.

cvTermList.name: Ilium
cvTermList.description: The ilium is the uppermost and largest bone of the pelvis, and appears in most vertebrates including mammals and birds, but not bony fish. All reptiles have an ilium except snakes, although some snake species have a tiny bone which is considered to be an ilium.

cvTermList.name: Sacrum
cvTermList.description: In vertebrate anatomy the sacrum (plural sacrums or sacra) is a large, triangular bone at the base of the spine and at the upper and back part of the pelvic cavity, where it is inserted like a wedge between the two hip bones. Its upper part connects with the last lumbar vertebra, and bottom part with the coccyx (tailbone). It consists of usually five initially unfused vertebrae which begin to fuse between ages 16 and 18 and are usually completely fused into a single bone by age 34.

cvTermList.name: Humerus
cvTermList.description: The humerus is a long bone in the arm or forelimb that runs from the shoulder to the elbow.

cvTermList.name: Fibula
cvTermList.description: The bone of the lower leg lateral to and smaller than the tibia. In proportion to its length, it is the most slender of the long bones.

cvTermList.name: Arm
cvTermList.description: In human anatomy, the arm is the part of the upper limb between the shoulder and the elbow joints.

cvTermList.name: Forearm
cvTermList.description: The forearm is the structure and distal region of the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

cvTermList.name: Leg
cvTermList.description: The inferior part of the lower extremity between the knee and the ankle.

cvTermList.name: Mouth floor
cvTermList.description: Floor of Mouth.

cvTermList.name: Axilla
cvTermList.description: The axilla (or armpit, underarm, or oxter) is the area on the human body directly under the joint where the arm connects to the shoulder. It also provides the under arm sweat gland.

cvTermList.name: Rib
cvTermList.description: In vertebrate anatomy, ribs (Latin costae) are the long curved bones which form the rib cage. In most vertebrates, ribs surround the chest, enabling the lungs to expand and thus facilitate breathing by expanding the chest cavity. They serve to protect the lungs, heart, and other internal organs of the thorax.

cvTermList.name: Labia
cvTermList.description: The labia are anatomical structures that are part of the female genitalia; they are the major externally visible portions of the vulva. In humans, there are two pairs of labia: the outer labia, or labia majora are larger and fattier, while the labia minora are folds of skin often concealed within the outer labia. The labia surround and protect the clitoris and the openings of the vagina and urethra.

cvTermList.name: Phalanx
cvTermList.description: In anatomy, phalanx bones (plural phalanges) are those that form the fingers and toes. In primates such as humans and monkeys, the thumb and big toe have two phalanges, while the other fingers and toes consist of three. Phalanges are classified as long bones.

cvTermList.name: Palate
cvTermList.description: The structure that forms the roof of the mouth. It consists of the anterior hard palate (hard palate) and the posterior soft palate (soft palate).

cvTermList.name: Hand
cvTermList.description: A hand is a prehensile, multi-fingered extremity located at the end of an arm or forelimb of primates such as humans, chimpanzees, monkeys, and lemurs.

cvTermList.name: Upper limb
cvTermList.description: The region of the upper limb in animals, extending from the deltoid region to the hand, and including the arm, axilla, and shoulder.

cvTermList.name: Lower limb
cvTermList.description: The region of the lower limb in animals, extending from the gluteal region to the foot, and including the buttocks, hip, and leg.

cvTermList.name: Face
cvTermList.description: The anterior portion of the head that includes the skin, muscles, and structures of the forehead, eyes, nose, mouth, cheeks, and jaw.

cvTermList.name: Maxilla
cvTermList.description: One of a pair of irregularly shaped bones that form the upper jaw. A maxillary bone provides tooth sockets for the superior teeth, forms part of the orbit, and contains the maxillary sinus.

cvTermList.name: Metacarpus
cvTermList.description: The region of the hand between the wrist and the fingers.

cvTermList.name: Ankle
cvTermList.description: The region of the lower limb between the foot and the leg.

cvTermList.name: Knee
cvTermList.description: The knee joint joins the thigh with the leg and consists of two articulations: one between the femur and tibia, and one between the femur and patella.

cvTermList.name: Metatarsus
cvTermList.description: The part of the foot between the tarsa and the toes.

cvTermList.name: Elbow
cvTermList.description: The human elbow is the region surrounding the elbow joint the ginglymus or hinge joint in the middle of the arm. Three bones form the elbow joint: the humerus of the upper arm, and the paired radius and ulna of the forearm.

cvTermList.name: Back
cvTermList.description: The human back is the large posterior area of the human body, rising from the top of the buttocks to the back of the neck and the shoulders.

cvTermList.name: Buttock
cvTermList.description: The buttocks (singular: buttock, also butt) are two rounded portions of the anatomy, located on the posterior of the pelvic region of apes and humans, and many other bipeds or quadrupeds, and comprise a layer of fat superimposed on the gluteus maximus and gluteus medius muscles.

cvTermList.name: Mandible
cvTermList.description: The largest and strongest bone of the face constituting the lower jaw. It supports the lower teeth.

cvTermList.name: Hip
cvTermList.description: The projecting part on each side of the body, formed by the side of the pelvis and the top portion of the femur.

cvTermList.name: Pelvis
cvTermList.description: The space or compartment surrounded by the pelvic girdle (bony pelvis). It is subdivided into the greater pelvis and lesser pelvis. The pelvic girdle is formed by the pelvic bones and sacrum.

cvTermList.name: Uvea
cvTermList.description: The pigmented vascular coat of the eyeball, consisting of the choroid; ciliary body; and iris, which are continuous with each other.

cvTermList.name: Shoulder
cvTermList.description: The human shoulder is made up of three bones: the clavicle (collarbone), the scapula (shoulder blade), and the humerus (upper arm bone) as well as associated muscles, ligaments and tendons.

cvTermList.name: Renal pelvis
cvTermList.description: The flattened, funnel shaped expansion connecting the ureter to the kidney calices.

cvTermList.name: Maxillary sinus
cvTermList.description: The air space located in the body of the maxillary bone near each cheek. Each maxillary sinus communicates with the middle passage (meatus) of the nasal cavity on the same side.

cvTermList.name: Conjunctiva
cvTermList.description: The mucous membrane that covers the posterior surface of the eyelids and the anterior pericorneal surface of the eyeball.

cvTermList.name: Middle ear
cvTermList.description: The space and structures directly internal to the tympanic membrane and external to the inner ear (labyrinth). Its major components include the auditory ossicles and the Eustachian tube that connects the cavity of middle ear (tympanic cavity) to the upper part of the throat.

cvTermList.name: Nipple
cvTermList.description: The conic organs which usually give outlet to milk from the mammary glands.

cvTermList.name: Pancreatic juice
cvTermList.description: The fluid containing digestive enzymes secreted by the pancreas in response to food in the duodenum.

cvTermList.name: Flank
cvTermList.description: The flesh between the last rib and the hip; the side.

cvTermList.name: Retroperitoneal space
cvTermList.description: An area occupying the most posterior aspect of the abdominal cavity. It is bounded laterally by the borders of the quadratus lumborum muscles and extends from the diaphragm to the brim of the true pelvis, where it continues as the pelvic extraperitoneal space.

cvTermList.name: Mediastinum
cvTermList.description: The mediastinum is an undelineated group of structures in the thorax, surrounded by loose connective tissue. It is the central compartment of the thoracic cavity. It contains the heart, the great vessels of the heart, the esophagus, the trachea, the phrenic nerve, the cardiac nerve, the thoracic duct, the thymus, and the lymph nodes of the central chest.

cvTermList.name: Groin
cvTermList.description: In human anatomy, the groin (the adjective is inguinal, as in Inguinal canal) areas are the two creases at the junction of the torso with the legs, on either side of the pubic area. This is also known as the medial (adductor) compartment of the thigh.

cvTermList.name: Autonomic ganglion
cvTermList.description: Clusters of neurons and their processes in the autonomic nervous system. In the autonomic ganglia, the preganglionic fibers from the central nervous system synapse onto the neurons whose axons are the postganglionic fibers innervating target organs. The ganglia also contain intrinsic neurons and supporting cells and preganglionic fibers passing through to other ganglia.

cvTermList.name: Scrotum
cvTermList.description: In some male mammals, the scrotum is a dual-chambered protuberance of skin and muscle, containing the testicles and divided by a septum. It is an extension of the perineum, and is located between the penis and anus.

cvTermList.name: Sella turcica
cvTermList.description: A bony prominence situated on the upper surface of the body of the sphenoid bone. It houses the pituitary gland.

cvTermList.name: Sphenoid bone
cvTermList.description: An irregular unpaired bone situated at the skull base and wedged between the frontal, temporal, and occipital bones (frontal bone; temporal bone; occipital bone). Sphenoid bone consists of a median body and three pairs of processes resembling a bat with spread wings. The body is hollowed out in its inferior to form two large cavities (sphenoid sinus).

cvTermList.name: Skull
cvTermList.description: The skeleton of the HEAD including the facial bones and the bones enclosing the brain.

cvTermList.name: Feces
cvTermList.description: Excrement from the intestines, containing unabsorbed solids, waste products, secretions, and bacteria of the digestive system.

cvTermList.name: Hypogastrium
cvTermList.description: The hypogastrium (alternative names including hypogastric region, public region and suprapubic region) is an area of the human abdomen located below the navel. The pubis bone constitutes its lower limit.

cvTermList.name: Craniopharyngeal duct
cvTermList.description: The craniopharyngeal canal, is a human anatomical feature sometimes found in the sphenoid bone opening to the sella turcica. It is a canal (a passage or channel) sometimes found extending from the anterior part of the fossa hypophyseos of the sphenoid bone to the under surface of the skull, and marks the original position of Rathke's pouch; while at the junction of the septum of the nose with the palate traces of the stomodeal end are occasionally present.

cvTermList.name: Ampulla of Vater
cvTermList.description: The ampulla of Vater, also known as the hepatopancreatic ampulla, is formed by the union of the pancreatic duct and the common bile duct.

cvTermList.name: Buccal mucosa
cvTermList.description: The buccal mucosa refers to the inside lining of the cheeks and is part of the lining mucosa of the oral mucosa.

cvTermList.name: Inframammary fold
cvTermList.description: Inframammary fold, inframammary crease or inframammary line is the feature of human anatomy which is a natural boundary of a breast from below, the place where the breast and the chest meet. The choice of the term depends on the prominence of the feature.

cvTermList.name: Subungual region
cvTermList.description: Region under a toenail or fingernail.

cvTermList.name: Vertebra
cvTermList.description: Any of the ring-shaped bony structures that constitute the spinal column and surround the spinal cord.

cvTermList.name: Retromolar trigone
cvTermList.description: The narrow band of mucosa that lies behind the mandibular molars and covers the ascending ramus.

cvTermList.name: Posterior cranial fossa
cvTermList.description: The infratentorial compartment that contains the cerebellum and brain stem. It is formed by the posterior third of the superior surface of the body of the sphenoid bone, by the occipital, the petrous, and mastoid portions of the temporal bone, and the posterior inferior angle of the parietal bone.

cvTermList.name: Paratesticular tissue
cvTermList.description: The soft tissues in close proximity to the testis.

cvTermList.name: Head and neck
cvTermList.description: For oncology, an area of the body generally construed to comprise the base of skull and facial bones, sinuses, orbits, salivary glands, oral cavity, oropharynx, larynx, thyroid, facial and neck musculature and lymph nodes draining these areas.

cvTermList.name: Parapharyngeal space
cvTermList.description: The parapharyngeal space (or lateral pharyngeal space) is a potential space in the head and the neck. It has clinical importance in otolaryngology due to parapharyngeal space tumours and parapharyngeal abscess developing in this area.

cvTermList.name: Paraganglia chromaffin
cvTermList.description: Small bodies containing chromaffin cells occurring outside of the adrenal medulla, most commonly near the sympathetic ganglia and in organs such as the kidney, liver, heart and gonads.

cvTermList.name: Cerebellar neuron
cvTermList.description: Neuron of the cerebellum.

cvTermList.name: Neural stem cell
cvTermList.description: Self-renewing cells that generate the main phenotypes of the nervous system in both the embryo and adult. Neural stem cells are precursors to both neurons and neuroglia.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral grey matter
cvTermList.description: Grey matter (or gray matter) is a major component of the central nervous system, consisting of neuronal cell bodies, neuropil (dendrites and unmyelinated axons), glial cells (astroglia and oligodendrocytes) and capillaries. Cerebral grey matter is distributed in the cerebrum.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral white matter
cvTermList.description: White matter consists mostly of glial cells and myelinated axons that transmit signals from one region of the cerebrum to another and between the cerebrum and lower brain centers. Cerebral white matter is distributed in the cerebrum.

cvTermList.name: Myelin sheath
cvTermList.description: The lipid-rich sheath surrounding axons in both the central and peripheral nervous systems. The myelin sheath is an electrical insulator and allows faster and more energetically efficient conduction of impulses. The sheath is formed by the cell membranes of glial cells (Schwann cells in the peripheral and oligodendroglia in the central nervous system). Deterioration of the sheath in demyelinating diseases is a serious clinical problem.

cvTermList.name: Lumbar vertebra
cvTermList.description: The lumbar vertebrae are the largest segments of the movable part of the vertebral column, and are characterized by the absence of the foramen transversarium within the transverse process, and by the absence of facets on the sides of the body. They are designated L1 to L5, starting at the top.

cvTermList.name: Myelencephalon
cvTermList.description: The most posterior portion of the hindbrain from which medulla oblongata is derived.

cvTermList.name: Hypodermis
cvTermList.description: Loose connective tissue lying under the dermis, which binds skin loosely to subjacent tissues. It may contain a pad of adipocytes, which vary in number according to the area of the body and vary in size according to the nutritional state.

cvTermList.name: Myeloid leukocyte
cvTermList.description: Leukocyte of myeloid origin.

cvTermList.name: Female germ cell
cvTermList.description: The female reproductive cells in multicellular organisms at various stages during gametogenesis.

cvTermList.name: Male germ cell
cvTermList.description: The male reproductive cells in multicellular organisms at various stages during gametogenesis.

cvTermList.name: Peripheral blood mononuclear cell
cvTermList.description: A peripheral blood cell with a single nucleus. This category includes lymphocytes and monocytes.

cvTermList.name: Neural tube
cvTermList.description: A tube of ectodermal tissue in an embryo that will give rise to the central nervous system, including the spinal cord and the brain. Lumen within the neural tube is called neural canal which gives rise to the central canal of the spinal cord and the ventricles of the brain.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral cortex endothelial cell
cvTermList.description: Endothelial cells forming the walls of the capillaries within the cerebral cortex.

cvTermList.name: Colon nerve tissue
cvTermList.description: Ganglia and peripheral neves found in the colon. Ganglia and postsynaptic neurons of the enteric nervous system are located in the lamina propia, muscularis mucosae, submucosa, muscularis externa, and subserosa of the alimentary canal from the esophagus to the anus. The neurons of the enteric nervous system are collected into two types of ganglia: myenteric (Auerbach's) and submucosal (Meissner's) plexuses. Myenteric plexuses are located between the inner and outer layers of the muscularis externa, while submucosal plexuses are located in the submucosa. In the colon, ganglion cells are found within the submucosa and muscularis externa.

cvTermList.name: Skin Melanocyte
cvTermList.description: Melanocytes found in skin.

cvTermList.name: Langerhans cell
cvTermList.description: Recirculating, dendritic, antigen-presenting cells containing characteristic racket-shaped granules (Birbeck granules). They are found principally in the stratum spinosum of the epidermis and are rich in Class II major histocompatibility complex molecules. Langerhans cells were the first dendritic cell to be described and have been a model of study for other dendritic cells (DCs), especially other migrating DCs such as dermal DCs and interstitial dendritic cells.

cvTermList.name: Skin Langerhans cell
cvTermList.description: Langerhans cell found in skin.

cvTermList.name: Breast adipocyte
cvTermList.description: Adipocytes found in the subcutaneous adipose tissue of breast. The breast consists of three main components, the skin, the subcutaneous adipose tissue and the functional glandular tissue that comprises both parenchyma and stroma.

cvTermList.name: Mammary gland myoepithelial cell
cvTermList.description: Myoepithelial cells found in the glandular epithelium of the mammary gland. The myoepithelial cells usually form a discontinuous layer between the luminal secretory cells and the basement membrane.

cvTermList.name: Myoepithelial cell
cvTermList.description: A contractile cell found between the secretory cells and basement membrane of exocrine glands. Each myoepithelial cell has long cytoplasmic processes that wrap around a secretory unit. The contraction of the myoepithelial processes forces the secretory product from the secretory unit into its duct.

cvTermList.name: Periodontium
cvTermList.description: The structures surrounding and supporting the tooth. Periodontium includes the gum (gingiva), the alveolar bone (alveolar process), the dental cementum, and the periodontal ligament.

cvTermList.name: Dorsal vagal nucleus
cvTermList.description: The dorsal nucleus of the vagus nerve (or posterior motor nucleus of vagus) is a cranial nerve nucleus for the vagus nerve in the medulla that lies under the floor of the fourth ventricle. It mostly serves parasympathetic vagal functions in the gastrointestinal tract, lungs, and other thoracic and abdominal vagal innervations.
synonyms: Dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve

cvTermList.name: Embryonic cerebral cortex
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult cerebral cortex. Corticogenesis is the process in which the cerebral cortex is created. The process is observed starting with embryonic days 10 to 11.5 (E10 to E11.5), continuing throughout the gestational period

cvTermList.name: Inferior olivari nucleus
cvTermList.description: The inferior olivary nucleus is the largest nucleus situated in the olivary body, part of the medulla oblongata.

cvTermList.name: Embryonic maxilla
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the fetal and adult maxilla.

cvTermList.name: Sebaceous gland
cvTermList.description: Small glands located within the epidermis, and associated with the hair follicle, that produce and secrete an oily substance that lubricates the skin and hair.

cvTermList.name: Lactiferous duct
cvTermList.description: A channel conveying the milk secreted by the lobes of the breast to and through the nipple.

cvTermList.name: Motor neuron
cvTermList.description: Motor neurons convey impulses from the CNS or ganglia to effector cells. Processes of these neurons are included in somatic efferent and visceral efferent nerve fibers. Somtic efferent neurons send voluntary impulses to skeletal muscles. Vvisceral efferent neurons transmit involuntary impulses to smooth muscle, cardiac condicting cells (Purkinje fibers), and glands.

cvTermList.name: Sensory neuron
cvTermList.description: Sensory neurons convey impulses from receptors to the CNS. Processes of these neurons are included in somatic afferent and visceral afferent nerve fibers. Somatic afferent fibers convey sensations of pain, temperature, touch, and pressure from the body surface. In addition, theses fibers convey pain and proprioception (nonconscious sensation) from organs within the body (e.g., muscles, tendons, and joints) to provide the brain with information related to the orientation of the body and limbs. Visceral afferent fibers transmit impulses of pain and other sensations from mucous membranes, glands, and blood vessels.

cvTermList.name: Dentate gyrus
cvTermList.description: A subsection of the hippocampal formation, described by Lorente de No, that composes the hilus of the dentate gyrus. A serrated strip of gray matter under the medial border of the hippocampus and in its depths. It is an archicortex which develops along the edge of the hippocampal fissure and which consists of molecular, granular, and polymorphic layers.

cvTermList.name: Ventral tegmental area
cvTermList.description: The ventral tegmentum (tegmentum is Latin for covering), better known as the ventral tegmental area (VTA), is a group of neurons located close to the midline on the floor of the midbrain (mesencephalon). The VTA is the origin of the dopaminergic cell bodies of the mesocorticolimbic dopamine system and is widely implicated in the drug and natural reward circuitry of the brain. It is important in cognition, motivation, drug addiction, intense emotions relating to love, and several psychiatric disorders. The VTA contains neurons that project to numerous areas of the brain, from the prefrontal cortex (PFC) to the caudal brainstem and several regions in between.

cvTermList.name: Para-aortic splanchnopleura
cvTermList.description: Embryonic structure precursor of the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region. The aorta-gonad-mesonephros is a region of embryonic mesoderm that develops during embryonic development from the para-aortic splanchnopleura in chick, mouse and human embryos. It has been suggested that this area, in particular the ventral wall of the dorsal aorta, is one of the primary origins of the definitive haematopoietic stem cell.

cvTermList.name: Cardia of stomach
cvTermList.description: The cardia is the anatomical term for the part of the stomach attached to the esophagus. The cardia begins immediately distal to the z-line of the gastroesophageal junction, where the squamous epithelium of the esophagus gives way to the columnar epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract.

cvTermList.name: Hemangioblast
cvTermList.description: Hemangioblast are the multipotent precursor cells that can differentiate into both hematopoietic and endothelial cells. In the yolk sac that can give rise to mesenchymal cells including erythrocytes and endothelial cells. There is now emerging evidence of hemangioblasts that continue to exist in the adult as circulating stem cells in the peripheral blood that can give rise to both endothelial cells and hematopoietic cells. These cells are thought to express both CD34 and CD133. These cells are likely derived from the bone marrow, and may even be derived from hematopoietic stem cells.

cvTermList.name: Gamma delta T cells
cvTermList.description: Gamma delta T cells represent a small subset of T cells that possess a distinct T-cell receptor (TCR) on their surface. Most T cells have a TCR composed of two glycoprotein chains called alpha and beta TCR chains (so called alpha beta T cells). In contrast, gamma delta T cells, have a TCR that is made up of one gamma chain and one delta chain. This group of T cells is usually much less common than alpha beta T cells, but are at their highest abundance in the gut mucosa, within a population of lymphocytes known as intraepithelial lymphocytes (IELs).

cvTermList.name: Neural progenitor cell
cvTermList.description: Neural progenitor cells are proliferative cells with a limited capacity for self-renewal and are often unipotent. Within the hippocampal subgranular cell layer, two different neural proliferative cells types exist: one that generates exclusively neuronal progeny and another that generates exclusively glial progeny. During development of the mammalian cerebral cortex, neurons are generated from two principal classes of neural progenitor cells: the apical progenitors and the basal progenitors or intermediate progenitor cells.

cvTermList.name: Marginal zone of spleen
cvTermList.description: The marginal zone is the region at the interface between the non-lymphoid red pulp and the lymphoid white-pulp of the spleen. The major role of marginal zone is to trap particulate antigen from the circulation and present the antigen to the lymphocytes of the spleen.

cvTermList.name: Cerebral cortex neuropil
cvTermList.description: Neuropil in the cerebral cortex.

cvTermList.name: Neuropil
cvTermList.description: Neuropil is a dense intricate feltwork of interwoven fine glial processes, fibrils, synaptic terminals, axons, and dendrites interspersed among the nerve cells in the gray matter of the central nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Colon endothelial cell
cvTermList.description: Endothelial cells found in colon.

cvTermList.name: Nasopharyngeal epithelial cell
cvTermList.description: Cell of the nasopharyngeal epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Bronchus epithelial cell
cvTermList.description: Cells of the pseudostratified bronchial epithelium.

cvTermList.name: Endothelial cell
cvTermList.description: Highly specialized epithelial cells that line the heart; blood vessels; and lymph vessels, forming the endothelium. They are polygonal in shape and joined together by tight junctions. The tight junctions allow for variable permeability to specific macromolecules that are transported across the endothelial layer.

cvTermList.name: Vascular endothelial cell
cvTermList.description: Highly specialized epithelial cells that line blood vessels and lymph vessels, forming the endothelium. They are polygonal in shape and joined together by tight junctions. The tight junctions allow for variable permeability to specific macromolecules that are transported across the endothelial layer.

cvTermList.name: Fetal telencephalon
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult telencephalon.

cvTermList.name: Visceral adipose tissue of abdominal region
cvTermList.description: Fatty tissue inside the abdominal cavity, including visceral fat and retroperitoneal fat. It is the most metabolically active fat in the body and easily accessible for lipolysis. Increased visceral fat is associated with metabolic complications of obesity.

cvTermList.name: Subcutaneous abdominal adipose tissue
cvTermList.description: Fatty tissue under the skin in the region of the abdomen.
synonyms: Subcutaneous adipose tissue of abdominal region

cvTermList.name: Interstitial cell of Cajal
cvTermList.description: This is a cell found in the gastrointestinal tract of mammals and serves as a pacemaker that triggers gut contraction. Interstitial cells of Cajal mediate inputs from the enteric nervous system to smooth muscle cells and are thought to be the cells from which gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) arise.

cvTermList.name: Regulatory T cell
cvTermList.description: A T cell which regulates overall immune responses as well as the responses of other T cell subsets through direct cell-cell contact and cytokine release. FOXP3-positive IL2RA-positive T cells that are crucial to maintain immune tolerance to self-antigens and avoid autoimmunity. Play an indispensable role in maintaining immunological unresponsiveness to self-antigens and in suppressing excessive immune responses deleterious to the host. Tregs are produced in the thymus as a functionally mature subpopulation of T cells and can also be induced from naive T cells in the periphery.

cvTermList.name: Aortico-pulmonary septum
cvTermList.description: Separates the aorta and pulmonary arteries and fuses with the interventricular septum within the heart during development. Is developmentally formed from neural crest, specifically the cardiac neural crest, and actively.

cvTermList.name: Myofibroblast cell
cvTermList.description: Cell that is in between a fibroblast and a smooth muscle cell in differentiation.

cvTermList.name: Migratory neural crest cell
cvTermList.description: Cell derived from the specialized ectoderm flanking each side of the embryonic neural plate, which after the closure of the neural tube, forms masses of cells that migrate out from the dorsal aspect of the neural tube to spread throughout the body.

cvTermList.name: Chondroblast
cvTermList.description: Skeletogenic cell that is typically non-terminally differentiated, secretes an avascular, GAG rich matrix; is not buried in cartilage tissue matrix, retains the ability to divide, located adjacent to cartilage tissue (including within the perichondrium), and develops from prechondroblast (and thus prechondrogenic) cell.

cvTermList.name: Acetabulum
cvTermList.description: The acetabulum is a concave surface of the pelvis. The head of the femur meets with the pelvis at the acetabulum, forming the hip joint. There are three bones of the os coxae (hip bone) that come together to form the acetabulum: the ischium, the ilium and the pubis.

cvTermList.name: Frontal bone
cvTermList.description: The frontal bone or os frontis is a bone in the human skull.

cvTermList.name: Middle cerebellar peduncle
cvTermList.description: The middle cerebellar peduncles (brachia pontis) are paired structures (left and right) that connect the cerebellum to the pons and are composed entirely of centripetal fibers, which arise from the cells of the nuclei pontis of the opposite side and end in the cerebellar cortex; the fibers are arranged in three fasciculi, superior, inferior, and deep.

cvTermList.name: Patella
cvTermList.description: The patella, also known as the kneecap or kneepan, is a thick, circular-triangular bone which articulates with the femur (thigh bone) and covers and protects the anterior articular surface of the knee joint. In humans, the patella is the largest sesamoid bone in the body. Babies are born with a patella of soft cartilage which begins to ossify into bone at about three years of age.

cvTermList.name: Talus bone
cvTermList.description: The talus bone, or ankle bone is a bone in the collection of bones in the foot called the tarsus. The tarsus forms the lower part of the ankle joint through its articulations with the lateral and medial malleoli of the two bones of the lower leg, the tibia and fibula. Within the tarsus, it articulates with the calcaneus below and navicular in front within the talocalcaneonavicular joint. Through these articulations, it transmits the entire weight of the body to the foot.

cvTermList.name: Nucleus accumbens
cvTermList.description: The nucleus accumbens, also known as the accumbens nucleus or as the nucleus accumbens septi is a region in the basal forebrain rostral to the preoptic area of the hypothalamus. The nucleus accumbens and the olfactory tubercle collectively form the ventral striatum, which is part of the basal ganglia. The nucleus accumbens has a significant role in the cognitive processing of motivation, pleasure, and reward and reinforcement learning, and hence has significant role in addiction. It plays a lesser role in fear, impulsivity, and the placebo effect. It is involved in the encoding of new motor programs as well.

cvTermList.name: Cumulus oocyte complex
cvTermList.description: The cumulus-oocyte complex in the antral follicle is formed by fully grown oocytes surrounded by compact layers of follicle cells. Oocyte growth and acquisition of  developmental competence occurs continuously throughout follicular development and is initiated as soon as the follicle enters the pool of growing follicles and is almost completed upon the antral follicle.

cvTermList.name: Lateral globus pallidus
cvTermList.description: The lateral globus pallidus (or external, GPe) receives a strong glutamatergic projection from the subthalamic nucleus. The two form a particular system: a coupled pacemaker. The axons of the external globus pallidum go essentially to the subthalamic nucleus. They go also to other elements of the basal ganglia system, the striatum, the substantia nigra pars reticulata, and the internal globus pallidus, where they release the neurotransmitter GABA. GPe is particular in comparison to the other elements of the set by the fact that it does not work as an output base of the basal ganglia (not sending axons to the thalamus) but as the main regulator of the basal ganglia system. It is sometimes used as a target for deep brain stimulation as a treatment for Parkinson's disease.

cvTermList.name: Medial globus pallidus
cvTermList.description: The medial globus pallidus (or internal, GPi) is one of the output nuclei of the basal ganglia (the other being the substantia nigra pars reticulata). The GABA-containing neurons send their axons to specific nuclei of the dorsal thalamus (VA and VL), to the centromedian complex and to the pedunculopontine complex.

cvTermList.name: Deltoid muscle
cvTermList.description: In human anatomy, the deltoid muscle is the muscle forming the rounded contour of the shoulder. Anatomically, it appears to be made up of three distinct sets of fibers though electromyography suggests that it consists of at least seven groups that can be independently coordinated by the central nervous system.

cvTermList.name: Peritubular myoid cell
cvTermList.description: The flattened smooth myoepithelial cells of mesodermal origin that lie just outside the basal lamina of the seminiferous tubule.

cvTermList.name: Prefrontal cortex
cvTermList.description: The anterior part of the frontal lobes of the brain, lying in front of the motor and premotor areas. This brain region has been implicated in planning complex cognitive behaviors, personality expression, decision making and moderating correct social behavior. The basic activity of this brain region is considered to be orchestration of thoughts and actions in accordance with internal goals. The most typical psychological term for functions carried out by the pre-frontal cortex area is executive function. Executive function relates to abilities to differentiate among conflicting thoughts, determine good and bad, better and best, same and different, future consequences of current activities, working toward a defined goal, prediction of outcomes, expectation based on actions, and social 'control' (the ability to suppress urges that, if not suppressed, could lead to socially-unacceptable outcomes). Many authors have indicated an integral link between a person's personality and the functions of the prefrontal cortex

cvTermList.name: Stomach fundus
cvTermList.description: In classical anatomy, the stomach is divided into four sections, and the fundus is formed by the upper curvature of the organ.

cvTermList.name: Pylorus
cvTermList.description: The pylorus, or pyloric part, is the region of the stomach that connects to the duodenum (not to be confused with the pyloric glands, which are analogous to the gastric glands (although currently referred to as the fundic glands)). The pylorus is considered as having two parts, the pyloric antrum (opening to the body of the stomach) and the pyloric canal (opening to the duodenum). The pyloric canal ends as the pyloric orifice, which marks the junction between the stomach and the duodenum. The orifice is surrounded by a sphincter, a band of muscle, called the pyloric sphincter. In classical anatomy, the stomach is divided into four sections, and the pylorus is the lower section of the organ that facilitates emptying the contents into the small intestine.

cvTermList.name: Substantia nigra pars compacta
cvTermList.description: Regional part of substantia nigra consisting of a densely packed region of cells, more or less dorsal to the pars reticulata, but extending into the pars reticulata in some species. The dominant neurotransmitter used by pars compacta neurons is dopamine. Pars compacta neurons are pigmented in many species.

cvTermList.name: Substantia nigra pars reticulata
cvTermList.description: Regional part of substantia nigra consisting of loosely packed cells, generally located ventral and lateral to the pars compacta. Many cells in this region use GABA as a neurotransmitter.

cvTermList.name: Vena cava
cvTermList.description: Any of the veins that carries deoxygenated blood from a part of the body into the right atrium of the heart.

cvTermList.name: Endometrial glandular cell
cvTermList.description: A glandular epithelial cell of the endometrium

cvTermList.name: Subcutaneous adipose tissue
cvTermList.description: A portion of adipose tissue that is part of the hypodermis, beneath the dermis.

cvTermList.name: Fetal intestine
cvTermList.description: Fetal structure that gives rise to adult intestine

cvTermList.name: Trigeminal ganglion
cvTermList.description: The trigeminal ganglion (or Gasserian ganglion, or semilunar ganglion, or Gasser's ganglion) is a sensory ganglion of the trigeminal nerve (CN V) that occupies a cavity (Meckel's cave) in the dura mater, covering the trigeminal impression near the apex of the petrous part of the temporal bone

cvTermList.name: Primary oocyte
cvTermList.description: A primary oocyte is an oocyte that has not completed female meosis I

cvTermList.name: Secondary oocyte
cvTermList.description: A secondary oocyte is an oocyte that has not completed meiosis II

cvTermList.name: Pachytene spermatocyte
cvTermList.description: Primary spermatocyte in the third stage of prophase I of meiosis during which the homologous chromosomes are closely paired and crossing-over takes place.

cvTermList.name: Pharyngeal mucosa
cvTermList.description: A mucosa that is part of a pharynx

cvTermList.name: CD4-positive helper T cell
cvTermList.description: A CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell that cooperates with other lymphocytes via direct contact or cytokine release to initiate a variety of immune functions.

cvTermList.name: CD8-Positive T-Lymphocytes
cvTermList.description: A critical subpopulation of regulatory T-lymphocytes involved in MHC Class I-restricted interactions. They include both cytotoxic T-lymphocytes and CD8+ suppressor T-lymphocytes

cvTermList.name: Superior surface of tongue
cvTermList.description: Superior surface of the tongue with papillae
synonyms: Superior surface of the tongue with papilla

cvTermList.name: Type I NK T cell
cvTermList.description: An alpha-beta T cell expressing NK cell markers that is CD1d restricted and expresses specific V-alpha chains. NK T cells of this type recognize the glycolipid alpha-galactosylceramide in the context of CD1d

cvTermList.name: Thymic cortex
cvTermList.description: The outer part of a thymus lobule that surrounds the medulla and is composed of closely packed lymphocytes

cvTermList.name: Cortical thymic epithelial cell
cvTermList.description: An epithelial cell of the cortical portion of the thymus. Epithelial cells in this region are required for positive selection of CD8-positive T cells

cvTermList.name: Cortical thymic dendritic cell CD11c-positive
cvTermList.description: Thymic cortex dendritic cells that expressed CD11c
synonyms: Cortical thymic dendritic cell CD11c positive

cvTermList.name: Cortical thymic dendritic cell CD303-positive
cvTermList.description: Thymic cortex dendritic cells that expressed CD303
synonyms: Cortical thymic dendritic cell CD303 positive

cvTermList.name: Cortical thymic dendritic cell CD209-positive
cvTermList.description: Thymic cortex dendritic cells that expressed CD209
synonyms: Cortical thymic dendritic cell CD209 positive

cvTermList.name: Gingival crevicular fluid
cvTermList.description: Gingival crevicular fluid (GCF) is a complex mixture of substances derived from serum, host inflammatory cells, structural cells of the periodontium, and oral bacteria. GCF originates from the vessels of the gingival plexus of blood vessels and flows through the external basement membrane and the junctional epithelium to reach the gingival sulcus.

cvTermList.name: Heel bone
cvTermList.description: Bone of the tarsus of the foot which constitutes the heel
